ion     = Middle States Association, Middle States Association International Credential, Absolute Charter from New York State, Green Schools Alliance<ref name=quick />\n| rival             = \n| mascot            = \n| mascot_image      = \n| sports            = \n| patron            = \n| team_name         = Cosmos\n| nickname          = \n| colours           = \n| colors            = Navy\n| yearbook          = Emerging Voices\n| publication       = \n| newspaper         = \n| opened            = 1992\n| established       = Upper School, 1991<br>Lower School, 2006<ref name=quick />\n| founded           = \n| status            = \n| closed            = \n| students          = \n| sixth_form_students = \n| pupils            = Upper School: 344<br>Lower School: 139\n| alumni            = \n| nobel_laureates   = \n| enrollment        =\n| gradeK            = \n| grade1            = \n| grade2            = \n| grade3            = \n| grade4            = \n| grade5            = \n| grade6            = \n| grade7            = \n| grade8            = \n| grade9            = \n| grade10           = \n| grade11           = \n| grade12           = \n| grade13           = \n| other_grade_label = \n| other             = \n| communities       = \n| feeder_schools           = \n| free_label        = \n| free_text         = \n| free_label1       = \n| free_text1        = \n| free_label2       = \n| free_text2        = \n| free_label3       = \n| free_text3        = \n| free_label4       = \n| free_text4        = \n| free_label5       = \n| free_text5        = \n| footnotes         = \n| picture           = \n| homepage          = {{url|ross.org}}\n}}\n\n'''Ross School''' is a private school K-12 school located in the [[East Hampton (town), New York|Town of East Hampton]], on [[Long Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]]. Named after her late husband [[Steven J. Ross]], the school was founded in 1991 by Courtney Sale Ross as a day school for her daughter and several friends. Originally offering pre-nursery, nursery, and pre-kindergarten programs, the school discontinued these in September 2020<ref>{{cite web |last1=Garrison |first1=Virginia |title=Ross School To End Programs For Youngest Students |url=https://www.27east.com/east-hampton-press/ross-school-to-end-programs-for-youngest-students-1669510/ |publisher=East Hampton Press |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>. It transitioned to a boarding school in 2010 after Ms. Ross discontinued private funding. \n\nA majority of the student body is international, with the highest-represented nations including Brazil, China and Russia. Head of School Bill O'Hearn has served in similar positions at the [[Beijing City International School]] in China and the [[Aga Khan Academy]] in Mombasa, Kenya.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sampson |first1=Christine |title=Former Head of School Returns to Ross |url=https://www.easthamptonstar.com/2019815/former-head-school-returns-ross |publisher=The East Hampton Star |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Curriculum==\nRoss School's curriculum is based on world cultural history and the evolution of consciousness and reflects the collaborative work of its founding mentors, mathematician [[Ralph Abraham (mathematician)|Ralph Abraham]] and cultural historian [[William Irwin Thompson]]. Cultural history is integrated with other academic subjects, such as language arts, math, and science, at every grade level.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Delatiner |first1=Barbara |title=A Garden of Learning, Growing Like a Weed?; The Ross School Discovers That Gobs of Money and Good Intentions Can't Buy Unopposed Expansion |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/04/30/nyregion/garden-learning-growing-like-weed-ross-school-discovers-that-gobs-money-good.html?login=smartlock&auth=login-smartlock |publisher=New York Times |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\nIn 2018, the Ross School achieved the founder's original vision by closing its five-building Lower School location in Bridgehampton and moving the early childhood and elementary grades to the Upper School campus in Wainscott. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Sampson |first1=Christine |title=Ross School Will Consolidate Lower School, Upper School Campuses |url=https://sagharborexpress.com/ross-school-will-consolidate-lower-school-upper-school-campuses/ |publisher=Sag Harbor Express |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Riley |first1=Cailin |title=Former Ross School Lower Campus In Bridgehampton Goes On The Market |url=mpton-gohttps://www.27east.com/southampton-press/former-ross-school-lower-campus-in-bridgehaes-on-the-market-1590789/ |publisher=Southampton Press |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000 the school proposed a 50-building, {{Convert|600000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} expansion to its {{Convert|140|acre|km2|adj=on}} campus which would have made it one of the biggest complexes in the Hamptons.  Enraged environmentalists charged that Courtney Ross was polluting the debate by paying to protest proposed expansion of the [[Long Island Central Pine Barrens]] protections into East Hampton.<ref>[http://www.pinebarrens.org/pdfs/Newsletters/spring00.pdf Largest Project Ever Proposed for South Fork - The Pine Line - Spring/Summer 2000]</ref>  The school eventually backed down on the expansion and in 2006 the same critics of this expansion were to applaud its \"green\" initiatives.\n\n== Summer events and programs==\nThe Ross School hosts an Annual Starlight Ball in June which has featured [[Aretha Franklin]], the [[Jonas Brothers]], [[Martha Stewart]], [[Cyndi Lauper]] and \u201cSaturday Night Live\u2019s\u201d [[Seth Meyers]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Seay |first1=Kendra |title=The Annual Club Starlight Ball For Ross School In East Hampton |url=https://guestofaguest.com/hamptons/events/the-annual-club-starlight-ball-for-ross-school-in-east-hampton |publisher=guestofaguest.com |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref> The largest event to date was held in 2007: a series of five musical concerts entitled \"Social @ Ross\" with [[Prince (musician)|Prince]]; [[Dave Matthews]] and [[Tim Reynolds]]; [[Billy Joel]]; [[James Taylor]] and [[Tom Petty]] and the Heartbreakers. The price of a ticket to the series was $15,000.<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/story?id=3371477&page=1&CMP=OTC-RSSFeeds0312 Only in the Hamptons: a $15,000 Rock Concert Rich and Famous Drop $15,000 for Five-Act Concert Series]</ref>\n\nThe school offers summer programs, including College Prep, English as a second language, marine science, design, mandarin immersion, mathematics, and tennis.\n\n==Ross Institute==\nIn 1966, Courtney Sale Ross founded Ross Institute for Advanced Study and Innovation in Education. The Institute provides training and certification for teachers interested in establishing schools based on the Ross School model.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ross Institute |url=https://vimeo.com/rossinstitute/about |website=Vimeo |publisher=Vimeo |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n;Alumni\n*[[Alexa Ray Joel]], singer\n*[[Scott Disick]], reality television star\n*[[Victoria de Lesseps]], artist\n*[[Tessa Gr\u00e4fin von Walderdorff]], socialite\n*The grandchildren of [[Dame Julie Andrews]] (Hope Hamilton and Sam Hamilton)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ross.org Official page]\n* [http://rossinstitute.org/ Ross Institute]\n* [http://summercamp.ross.org/ Ross School Summer Camp]\n* [http://www.boardingschools.com/school-profile/Ross-School The Association of Boarding Schools profile]\n\n[[Category:Private high schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:East Hampton (town), New York]]\n[[Category:Private elementary schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Private middle schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Schools in Suffolk County, New York]]\n", "text_old": "{{advert|date=August 2015}}\n{{more citations needed|date=August 2015}}\n{{copypaste|date=August 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox school\n| name              = Ross School\n| native_name       = \n| latin_name        = \n| image             = File:Ross School Spiral Logo Centered.gif\n| image_size         = \n| caption           = \n| location          = East Hampton, New York\n| streetaddress     = 18 Goodfriend Drive\n| region            = NorthEast\n| city              = East Hampton\n| state             = New York\n| province          = \n| county            = Suffolk\n| postcode          = \n| postalcode        = \n| zipcode           = 11937\n| country           = United States\n| country1          = \n| coordinates       = {{Coord|40.969408|-72.2406|type:edu_region:US|display=inline,title}}\n| school_number      = \n| schoolboard       = \n| district          = \n| authority         = \n| religion          = \n| denomination      = \n| oversight         = \n| affiliation       = Independent Day (Grades Pre-Nursery\u201312, and Boarding School (Grades 6\u201312)\n| superintendent    = \n| trustee           = \n| founder           = Courtney Sale Ross<br>[[Steven J. Ross]]\n| specialist        = \n| president         =\n| headteacher       = \n| head_label        = \n| head              = \n| chairperson       = \n| principal         = Bill O' Hearn\n| principal_label   = Head of Upper School\n| principal1        = Jeanette Tyndall\n| principal_label1  = Head of Lower School\n| principal2        = \n| principal3        = \n| principal4        = \n| dean              = \n| administrator     = \n| rector            = \n| chaplain          = \n| director          = \n| staff             = \n| ranking           = \n| bar_pass_rate     = \n| faculty           = Upper School:<br> 55 full-time, 10 part-time<br>Lower School:<br> 20 full-time, 9 part-time<ref name=quick>{{cite web |url=http://www.ross.org/facts |title=Quick Facts | publisher=Ross School |accessdate=March 31, 2014}}</ref>\n| teaching_staff    = \n| school_roll              = \n| MOE               = \n| ceeb              = \n| school_code       = \n| LEA               = \n| ofsted            = \n| test_average       = \n| test_name          = \n| national_ranking  = \n| classes           = \n| classes_offered   = \n| average_class_size    = \n| ratio             = \n| SAT               = Average score: 1850\n| SAT_year    = 1992\n| ACT               = \n| graduates         = \n| gender            = Co-ed\n| lower_age         = \n| upper_age         = \n| houses            = \n| schooltype        = Boarding, Day\n| fundingtype       = Private\n| type              = \n| system            = \n| fees              = \n| tuition           = '''Boarding''': (Grade 6-Post Graduate): $76,870 (Domestic); $79,030 (International); $71,870 (5-day)\n\n'''Day''': (Grade 5-Post Graduate): $44,110; \n(PreNursery-Kindergarten): $16,160-$36,390\n| revenue           = \n| endowment         = \n| budget            = \n| products          = \n| grades            = Upper School: Grades 7&ndash;12<br>Lower School, Pre-Nursery&ndash;Grade 6\n| age_range         = \n| medium_of_language            = \n| language          = \n| classrooms        = \n| campus            = \n| campus_size       = \n| campus_type       = \n| hours_in_day      = \n| athletics         = Grades 9\u201312: Baseball (Boys)<br>Basketball (Boys and Girls)<br>Cross Country (Boys and Girls)<br>Golf (Co-ed)<br>Sailing (Co-ed)<br>Soccer (Boys)<br>Softball (Girls)<br>Tennis (Boys and Girls)<br>Track and Field (Boys and Girls)<br>Volleyball (Girls)<br>Grades 7\u20138: Baseball (Boys)<br>Basketball (Boys and Girls)<br>Soccer (Boys and Girls)<br>Softball (Girls)<br>Volleyball (Girls)\n| athletics_conference        = \n| slogan            = \n| song              = \n| fight_song         = \n| motto             = Know Thyself in Order to Serve<ref name=quick />\n| accreditation     = Middle States Association, Middle States Association International Credential, Absolute Charter from New York State, Green Schools Alliance<ref name=quick />\n| rival             = \n| mascot            = \n| mascot_image      = \n| sports            = \n| patron            = \n| team_name         = Cosmos\n| nickname          = \n| colours           = \n| colors            = Navy\n| yearbook          = Emerging Voices\n| publication       = \n| newspaper         = \n| opened            = 1992\n| established       = Upper School, 1991<br>Lower School, 2006<ref name=quick />\n| founded           = \n| status            = \n| closed            = \n| students          = \n| sixth_form_students = \n| pupils            = Upper School: 344<br>Lower School: 139\n| alumni            = \n| nobel_laureates   = \n| enrollment        =\n| gradeK            = \n| grade1            = \n| grade2            = \n| grade3            = \n| grade4            = \n| grade5            = \n| grade6            = \n| grade7            = \n| grade8            = \n| grade9            = \n| grade10           = \n| grade11           = \n| grade12           = \n| grade13           = \n| other_grade_label = \n| other             = \n| communities       = \n| feeder_schools           = \n| free_label        = \n| free_text         = \n| free_label1       = \n| free_text1        = \n| free_label2       = \n| free_text2        = \n| free_label3       = \n| free_text3        = \n| free_label4       = \n| free_text4        = \n| free_label5       = \n| free_text5        = \n| footnotes         = \n| picture           = \n| homepage          = {{url|ross.org}}\n}}\n\n'''Ross School''' is a private school K-12 school located in the [[East Hampton (town), New York|Town of East Hampton]], on [[Long Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]]. Named after her late husband [[Steven J. Ross]], the school was founded in 1991 by Courtney Sale Ross as a day school for her daughter and several friends. Originally offering pre-nursery, nursery, and pre-kindergarten programs, the school discontinued these in September 2020<ref>{{cite web |last1=Garrison |first1=Virginia |title=Ross School To End Programs For Youngest Students |url=https://www.27east.com/east-hampton-press/ross-school-to-end-programs-for-youngest-students-1669510/ |publisher=East Hampton Press |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>. It transitioned to a boarding school in 2010 after Ms. Ross discontinued private funding. \n\nA majority of the student body is international, with the highest-represented nations including Brazil, China and Russia. Head of School Bill O'Hearn has served in similar positions at the [[Beijing City International School]] in China and the [[Aga Khan Academy]] in Mombasa, Kenya.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sampson |first1=Christine |title=Former Head of School Returns to Ross |url=https://www.easthamptonstar.com/2019815/former-head-school-returns-ross |publisher=The East Hampton Star |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Curriculum==\nRoss School's curriculum is based on world cultural history and the evolution of consciousness and reflects the collaborative work of its founding mentors, mathematician [[Ralph Abraham (mathematician)|Ralph Abraham]] and cultural historian [[William Irwin Thompson]]. Cultural history is integrated with other academic subjects, such as language arts, math, and science, at every grade level.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Delatiner |first1=Barbara |title=A Garden of Learning, Growing Like a Weed?; The Ross School Discovers That Gobs of Money and Good Intentions Can't Buy Unopposed Expansion |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/04/30/nyregion/garden-learning-growing-like-weed-ross-school-discovers-that-gobs-money-good.html?login=smartlock&auth=login-smartlock |publisher=New York Times |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\nIn 2018, the Ross School achieved the founder's original vision by closing its five-building Lower School location in Bridgehampton and moving the early childhood and elementary grades to the Upper School campus in Wainscott. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Sampson |first1=Christine |title=Ross School Will Consolidate Lower School, Upper School Campuses |url=https://sagharborexpress.com/ross-school-will-consolidate-lower-school-upper-school-campuses/ |publisher=Sag Harbor Express |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Riley |first1=Cailin |title=Former Ross School Lower Campus In Bridgehampton Goes On The Market |url=mpton-gohttps://www.27east.com/southampton-press/former-ross-school-lower-campus-in-bridgehaes-on-the-market-1590789/ |publisher=Southampton Press |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000 the school proposed a 50-building, {{Convert|600000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} expansion to its {{Convert|140|acre|km2|adj=on}} campus which would have made it one of the biggest complexes in the Hamptons.  Enraged environmentalists charged that Courtney Ross was polluting the debate by paying to protest proposed expansion of the [[Long Island Central Pine Barrens]] protections into East Hampton.<ref>[http://www.pinebarrens.org/pdfs/Newsletters/spring00.pdf Largest Project Ever Proposed for South Fork - The Pine Line - Spring/Summer 2000]</ref>  The school eventually backed down on the expansion and in 2006 the same critics of this expansion were to applaud its \"green\" initiatives.\n\n== Summer events and programs==\nThe Ross School hosts an Annual Starlight Ball in June which has featured [[Aretha Franklin]], the [[Jonas Brothers]], [[Martha Stewart]], [[Cyndi Lauper]] and \u201cSaturday Night Live\u2019s\u201d [[Seth Meyers]]. The largest event to date was held in 2007: a series of five musical concerts entitled \"Social @ Ross\" with [[Prince (musician)|Prince]]; [[Dave Matthews]] and [[Tim Reynolds]]; [[Billy Joel]]; [[James Taylor]] and [[Tom Petty]] and the Heartbreakers. The price of a ticket to the series was $15,000.<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/story?id=3371477&page=1&CMP=OTC-RSSFeeds0312 Only in the Hamptons: a $15,000 Rock Concert Rich and Famous Drop $15,000 for Five-Act Concert Series]</ref>\n\nThe school offers summer programs, including College Prep, English as a second language, marine science, design, mandarin immersion, mathematics, and tennis.\n\n==Ross Institute==\nIn 1966, Courtney Sale Ross founded Ross Institute for Advanced Study and Innovation in Education. The Institute provides training and certification for teachers interested in establishing schools based on the Ross School model.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ross Institute |url=https://vimeo.com/rossinstitute/about |website=Vimeo |publisher=Vimeo |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n;Alumni\n*[[Alexa Ray Joel]], singer\n*[[Scott Disick]], reality television star\n*[[Victoria de Lesseps]], artist\n*[[Tessa Gr\u00e4fin von Walderdorff]], socialite\n*The grandchildren of [[Dame Julie Andrews]] (Hope Hamilton and Sam Hamilton)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ross.org Official page]\n* [http://rossinstitute.org/ Ross Institute]\n* [http://summercamp.ross.org/ Ross School Summer Camp]\n* [http://www.boardingschools.com/school-profile/Ross-School The Association of Boarding Schools profile]\n\n[[Category:Private high schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:East Hampton (town), New York]]\n[[Category:Private elementary schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Private middle schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Schools in Suffolk County, New York]]\n", "name_user": "Margaretwmiller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSummer events and programs:added link to article about Starlight Ball", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ross_School_(East_Hampton,_New_York)"}
{"title_page": "Emeka Okafor", "text_new": "{{short description|American basketball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NBA biography\n| name = Emeka Okafor\n| image = Emeka Okafor Washington at Orlando 002.jpg\n| caption = Okafor during his tenure with the Washington Wizards\n| position = [[Center (basketball)|Center]] / [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 10\n| weight_lb = 252\n| league = [[Korean Basketball League]]\n| team = Ulsan Mobis Phoebus\n| number = 50\n| nationality = American\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1982|9|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Houston, Texas]]\n| high_school = [[Bellaire High School (Bellaire, Texas)|Bellaire]] ([[Bellaire, Texas]])\n| college = [[UConn Huskies men's basketball|UConn]] (2001\u20132004)\n| draft_year = 2004\n| draft_round = 1\n| draft_pick = 2\n| draft_team = [[Charlotte Bobcats]]\n| career_start = 2004\n| career_end = \n| years1 = {{nbay|2004|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2008|end}}\n| team1 = [[Charlotte Bobcats]]\n| years2 = {{nbay|2009|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2011|end}}\n| team2 = [[New Orleans Pelicans|New Orleans Hornets]]\n| years3 = {{nbay|2012|full=y}}\n| team3 = [[Washington Wizards]]\n| years4 = 2017\u20132018\n| team4 = [[Delaware 87ers]]\n| years5 = {{nbay|2017|end}}\n| team5 = New Orleans Pelicans\n| team6 = [[Ulsan Hyundai Mobis Phoebus]]\n| years6 = 2019\u2013present\n| highlights   = \n* [[NBA Rookie of the Year Award|NBA Rookie of the Year]] ({{nbay|2004|end}})\n* [[NBA All-Rookie First Team]] ({{nbay|2004|end}})\n* [[List of NCAA Men's Division I Basketball champions|NCAA champion]] ([[2004 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|2004]])\n* [[NCAA Final Four Most Outstanding Player]] ([[2004 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|2004]])\n* [[NABC Player of the Year|NABC Co-Player of the Year]] (2004)\n* Consensus first-team [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] ([[2004 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|2004]])\n* Third-team All-American \u2013 [[National Association of Basketball Coaches|NABC]] ([[2003 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|2003]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[NABC Defensive Player of the Year]] (2003, 2004)\n* [[Pete Newell Big Man Award]] (2004)\n* [[Big East Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year|Big East Player of the Year]] (2004)\n* 2\u00d7 First-team All-[[Big East Conference|Big East]] (2003, 2004)\n* {{nowrap|2\u00d7 Big East Defensive Player of the Year (2003, 2004)}}\n* [[List of NCAA Division I men's basketball season blocks leaders|NCAA blocks leader]] (2003)\n| bbr           = okafoem01\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport|Men's Basketball}}\n{{MedalCountry|the {{USA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2004 Summer Olympics|2004 Athens]] | [[Basketball at the 2004 Summer Olympics|United States]]}}\n}}\n'''Chukwuemeka Ndubuisi''' \"'''Emeka'''\" '''Okafor''' (born September 28, 1982) is an American professional [[basketball]] player who currently plays for the [[Ulsan Hyundai Mobis Phoebus]] of the [[Korean Basketball League]] (KBL). Okafor attended [[Bellaire High School (Bellaire, Texas)|Bellaire High School]] in [[Bellaire, Texas]] and the [[University of Connecticut]], where in 2004 he won a national championship. In his first season in the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) in 2004/05, Okafor was named [[NBA Rookie of the Year Award|Rookie of the Year]].\n\n==Early life==\nOkafor was born in [[Houston]], [[Texas]]. Both of his parents are natives of [[Nigeria]], and Emeka was the first member of his family born in the United States.<ref name=\"nbabio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/playerfile/emeka_okafor/bio/ |title=Emeka Okafor Stats, Video, Bio, Profile |work=NBA.com |accessdate=September 14, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140803182111/http://www.nba.com/playerfile/emeka_okafor/bio/ |archivedate=August 3, 2014 }}</ref> His father, Pius Okafor, is a member of the [[Igbo people|Igbo]] ethnic group.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/03/26/sports/2003-ncaa-tournament-true-student-athlete-academics-and-a-game-to-back-it-up.html |title=2003 N.C.A.A. TOURNAMENT: TRUE STUDENT ATHLETE; Academics, And a Game To Back It Up |work=NYTimes.com |first=Jere |last=Longman |date=March 26, 2003 |accessdate=September 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOkafor's family moved to [[Bartlesville, Oklahoma]] when he was young because his father worked for [[Phillips Petroleum Company]], headquartered in Bartlesville. While in Bartlesville, Okafor's father took his son to the Bartlesville YMCA to learn the game of basketball.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/stories/040604aac.html |title=Okafor Exemplifies Concept of 'Student-Athlete' |work=CSTV.com |date=April 6, 2004 |accessdate=September 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==High school career==\nOkafor played at Bellaire High School with future Oklahoma State star [[John Lucas III]]. Okafor averaged 22 points, 16 rebounds and 7 blocks in his senior season. Bellaire was 26\u20135 in that season, losing 56\u201342 in the third round of the 2001 [[University Interscholastic League|UIL]] state playoffs, to [[Willowridge High School (Houston)|Willowridge High School]] and future [[Texas Longhorns men's basketball|Texas]] standout [[T. J. Ford]]. This game is particularly notable, however, because it featured five players who would go on to play in an NCAA Final Four (Bellaire had Lucas and Okafor, while Willowridge featured Ford, Oklahoma State's [[Ivan McFarlin]] and Duke's [[Daniel Ewing]]). All five of these players would eventually go on to play at least a season in the NBA.\n\nOkafor flew under the recruiting radar for much of his high school career, but by the end of his senior year, Okafor was receiving late interest from top programs and chose to accept a scholarship at the [[University of Connecticut]], choosing the Huskies over [[University of Arkansas|Arkansas]] and [[Vanderbilt University|Vanderbilt]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lubbockonline.com/stories/042001/col_042001025.shtml|title=Bellaire's Okafor to sign with Connecticut - Lubbock Online - Lubbock Avalanche-Journal|website=lubbockonline.com}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nOkafor played for the University of Connecticut from 2001 to 2004 where he was teammates with [[Charlie Villanueva]], [[Marcus Williams (basketball, born 1985)|Marcus Williams]], [[Ben Gordon (basketball)|Ben Gordon]], [[Hilton Armstrong]] and [[Josh Boone (basketball)|Josh Boone]], who all went on to play in the NBA. He majored in [[finance]] during his time at Connecticut, and he graduated with honors after three years in May 2004 with a 3.8 [[Grade point average|GPA]]. Okafor was named the Academic All-American of the Year in 2004 for his work on and off the court.\n\nOkafor is noted for his impressive defensive ability, especially his shot-blocking. Although he was plagued by back problems for most of the 2003\u201304 season, Okafor led UConn to the program's second [[2004 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship Game|national title]] in six seasons. He was crowned as the [[NCAA]] tournament's [[NCAA Basketball Tournament Most Outstanding Player|Most Outstanding Player]]. In addition, Okafor led the nation in blocks that season and was also named National Defensive Player of the Year by the [[National Association of Basketball Coaches]]. He also received the [[Big East Men's Basketball Player of the Year|Big East Player of the Year]] award. Okafor graduated as Connecticut's leader in blocked shots with 441.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hoopshype.com/players/emeka_okafor.htm |title=HoopsHype Players \u2013 50 Emeka Okafor |work=HoopsHype.com |accessdate=September 14, 2014}}</ref> In light of his collegiate achievements, Okafor was made a member of the 2004 U.S. National Men's Basketball Team which represented the U.S. at the Olympics in Athens.\n\nOn February 5, 2007, he was inducted to the Husky Ring Of Honor at [[Harry A. Gampel Pavilion|Gampel Pavilion]] on the University of Connecticut campus in [[Storrs, Connecticut|Storrs]] during halftime of the men's basketball game against the [[Syracuse Orange]] as part of a ceremony which recognized personal accomplishments of 13 former players and 3 coaches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://depthoffieldphoto.wordpress.com/2008/07/23/huskies-of-honor/|title=Huskies of Honor|date=July 23, 2008|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==NBA career==\n\n===Charlotte Bobcats (2004\u20132009)===\nOn April 16, 2004, Okafor declared his eligibility for the [[2004 NBA draft]], giving up his one remaining year of college athletic eligibility. He did, however, receive his undergraduate degree in Accounting/Finance in three academic years. On June 24, Okafor was selected second overall in the draft, becoming the first ever draft pick by the expansion [[Charlotte Bobcats]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/hornets/news/draft_okafor_062404.html |title=Bobcats Select Emeka Okafor As First-Ever Rookie Draft Pick |work=NBA.com |date=June 24, 2004 |accessdate=September 14, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150606002430/http://www.nba.com/hornets/news/draft_okafor_062404.html |archivedate=June 6, 2015 }}</ref> The following day, he accepted an invitation to join the [[Dream Team IV|United States team]] for the [[2004 Summer Olympics]], which finished with the [[bronze medal]] in [[Athens]].\n\nThe [[2004\u201305 NBA season|2004\u201305 season]] was a successful campaign as Okafor coped well with the pressures of being the star rookie on an expansion franchise. Highlights of the season included recording 19 straight [[Double-doubles|double-double]]s from November 21 through January 1, and finishing seventh among [[Eastern Conference (NBA)|Eastern Conference]] forwards in [[National Basketball Association All-Star Game|NBA All-Star Game]] fan balloting with 408,082 votes, by far the highest number garnered by any [[rookie]] in 2005. At the end of the season, Okafor beat out his friend and former college teammate and roommate, [[Chicago Bulls]] guard [[Ben Gordon (basketball)|Ben Gordon]], to win the [[NBA Rookie of the Year Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=2053181 |title=Okafor named Rookie of Year |publisher=ESPN |date=May 5, 2005 |accessdate=September 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn June 24, 2005, the Bobcats picked up the option for the fourth year on Okafor's contract, as he quickly established himself as the face of the franchise, and a solid player for years to come. Okafor finished his rookie season with 44.7% [[field goal (basketball)|field goal]] percentage and per-game averages of 15.1 points, 10.9 rebounds (ranked 4th in the league<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/NBA_2005.html|title=2004-05 NBA Season Summary - Basketball-Reference.com|website=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>), and 1.7 blocks.\n\nIn the 2005 offseason, Okafor's weight increased from 260 to 280&nbsp;lbs. It was this weight gain which he felt caused him to have trouble rehabbing his early season ankle injury and forced him to sit out most of the [[2005\u201306 NBA season|2005\u201306 season]] with injuries to his ankle.<ref name=\"dailydime\">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/dailydime?page=dailydime-061125-26 |title=SPECIAL WEEKEND EDITION: Passing some hefty judgments |publisher=ESPN |date=November 26, 2006 |accessdate=September 14, 2014}}</ref> Nonetheless in the few games he played he was effective as he averaged a double-double for the second consecutive season. For the season he finished with averages of 13.2 points on 41.5% shooting, 10.0 rebounds and 1.9 blocks per game.\n\n[[File:Bobcats vs Pistons tip off.jpg|thumb|right|Okafor tipping-off against [[Rasheed Wallace]].]]\nDuring the offseason he continued his tutorials with [[Hakeem Olajuwon]], which he took up after his rookie season,<ref name=\"dailydime\" /> and lost the 20 pounds which he had gained for his second season. Okafor felt this weight loss gave him more energy and mobility. He led the Bobcats in rebounds per game, blocks per game, and field goal percentage. On December 29, 2006, in a home game against the Los Angeles Lakers, Emeka would record 22 points, 25 rebounds, and 4 blocks in over 51 minutes of play, in an epic 133\u2013124 triple overtime victory. He also had eight blocks in games against the Dallas Mavericks and Boston Celtics. On January 12, 2007, he would record an NBA season high ten blocks in a game against the New York Knicks. His ten blocks were the most ever recorded in a single game at Madison Square Garden. In that game, he was one rebound away from recording the first ever [[triple-double]] in franchise history, finishing with 20 pts, 10 blocks, 9 rebounds, and 3 steals.  Later in the season, he suffered an ankle injury which caused him to miss fifteen games. He finished the season averaging 14.4 points, 11.3 rebounds and 2.6 blocks in 67 games.\n\nPrior to the start of the 2007\u201308 season, Okafor turned down a contract extension with the Charlotte Bobcats worth an estimated US$60 million over five years. Despite turning down the contract, Okafor maintained that he indeed wanted to remain with the Bobcats. Despite feuding with head coach Sam Vincent throughout the season, Okafor still managed to average a double-double for the fourth consecutive season of his career. He also played in all 82 games of the regular season for the first time in his career. At the end of the season head coach Sam Vincent was fired by part-owner Michael Jordan saying in a statement: \"The decision to remove Sam as head coach after just one season was difficult, but it was a decision that had to be made because my first obligation is to do what is in the best interest of our team.\"\n\nDuring the off-season, the Bobcats' top priority was to re-sign Okafor. Through tough negotiations the Bobcats and Okafor eventually reached an agreement on a six-year, $72 million deal, the largest in franchise history. In a statement, Okafor voiced his pleasure with remaining in the organization: \"The Bobcats and the entire Charlotte community embraced me from day one, and it's exciting to enter this season with a Hall of Fame coach and teammates who are committed to winning.\"\n\nOkafor entered the 2008\u201309 season with active franchise-record streaks of 93 consecutive games played and 92 consecutive games started.\n\n===New Orleans Hornets (2009\u20132012)===\nOn July 28, 2009, Okafor was traded to the [[New Orleans Hornets]] in exchange for [[Tyson Chandler]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=4359609 |title=Sources: Hornets, Cats agree on deal |publisher=ESPN |date=July 28, 2009 |accessdate=September 14, 2014}}</ref> During the [[2010\u201311 NBA season|2010\u201311 season]], Okafor ended up making it to his first ever NBA playoff series against the [[Los Angeles Lakers]]. Ultimately, the Hornets lost their first-round series 4-2, with Okafor having a decrease in points and rebounding averages throughout the six games.\n\n===Washington Wizards (2012\u20132013)===\nOn June 20, 2012, Okafor was traded, along with [[Trevor Ariza]], to the [[Washington Wizards]] in exchange for [[Rashard Lewis]] and the 46th pick of the [[2012 NBA draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidehoops.com/blog/?p=10232|title=Hornets trade Emeka Okafor and Trevor Ariza to Wizards for Rashard Lewis :InsideHoops|website=www.insidehoops.com|access-date=July 3, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402112811/http://www.insidehoops.com/blog/?p=10232|archive-date=April 2, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Okafor went on to be named a finalist for the inaugural [[Twyman\u2013Stokes Teammate of the Year Award]] for his contributions with the team on and off the court.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/2013/news/06/09/first-twyman-stokes-award-billups/|title=Billups wins first Twyman-Stokes Award|first=Official|last=Release|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Injury recovery and free agency (2013\u20132017)===\nOn October 25, 2013, days before the start of the [[2013\u201314 NBA season|2013\u201314 season]], Okafor was traded, along with a [[Tyler Ennis (basketball)|2014 protected first-round draft pick]], to the [[Phoenix Suns]] in exchange for [[Marcin Gortat]], [[Shannon Brown]], [[Kendall Marshall]] and [[Malcolm Lee (basketball)|Malcolm Lee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/suns/news/suns-acquire-okafor-first-round-pick|title=Suns Acquire Okafor, First-Round Pick|work=NBA.com|publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc.|accessdate=October 25, 2013|date=October 25, 2013}}</ref> However, he missed the entire season due to a herniated disc in his neck that was discovered in September 2013, and remained unsigned throughout the [[2014\u201315 NBA season|2014\u201315 season]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/12114070/emeka-okafor-likely-delay-comeback-neck-injury-next-season|title=Okafor likely to wait on decision|first=Marc|last=Stein|date=January 2, 2015|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=January 7, 2015}}</ref> the [[2015\u201316 NBA season|2015\u201316 season]], and the [[2016\u201317 NBA season|2016\u201317 season]]. On May 30, 2017, Okafor was medically cleared to play.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hann|first=Lucas|url=https://www.clipsnation.com/2017/5/30/15716276/nba-free-agency-la-clippers-report-emeka-okafor-cleared-to-play-attempting-nba-comeback|title=Report: Emeka Okafor Cleared to Play, Attempting NBA Comeback|work=clipsnation.com|date=May 30, 2017|accessdate=September 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Philadelphia and Delaware (2017\u20132018)===\n[[File:Emeka Okafor 87ers.png|thumb|right|Okafor during his tenure with the [[Delaware 87ers]]]]\nOn September 25, 2017, Okafor signed with the [[Philadelphia 76ers]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sixers Sign Humphries, Okafor; Set Training Camp Roster|url=http://www.nba.com/sixers/news/sixers-sign-humphries-okafor-set-training-camp-roster|website=NBA.com|accessdate=September 25, 2017|date=September 25, 2017}}</ref> However, he was waived on October 14 after appearing in five preseason games.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sixers Waive Three Players|url=http://www.nba.com/sixers/news/sixers-waive-three-players|website=NBA.com|accessdate=October 14, 2017|date=October 14, 2017}}</ref> Later that month, he joined the [[Delaware 87ers]] of the [[NBA G League]].<ref name=undefeated/>\n\n===Return to New Orleans (2018)===\nOn February 3, 2018, Okafor signed a 10-day contract with the [[New Orleans Pelicans]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/pelicans/news/pelicans-sign-emeka-okafor-10-day-contract|title=Pelicans sign Emeka Okafor to 10-day contract|work=NBA.com|date=February 3, 2018|accessdate=February 3, 2018}}</ref> He made his Pelicans debut two days later, playing in the NBA for the first time since 2013. He played nine minutes and had three points and two rebounds in a 133\u2013109 loss to the [[Utah Jazz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400975539|title=Hood scores 30, Jazz win 6th straight, 133-109 over Pelicans|work=ESPN.com|date=February 5, 2018|accessdate=February 5, 2018}}</ref> He signed a second 10-day contract on February 14,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/pelicans/pelicans-sign-emeka-okafor-second-10-day-contract|title=Pelicans Sign Emeka Okafor to Second 10-Day Contract|work=NBA.com|date=February 14, 2018|accessdate=February 14, 2018}}</ref> and a rest-of-season contract on February 26.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/pelicans/pelicans-sign-emeka-okafor|title=Pelicans Sign Emeka Okafor|work=NBA.com|date=February 26, 2018|accessdate=February 26, 2018}}</ref> Filling in for the injured [[DeMarcus Cousins]], Okafor averaged 4.4 points, 4.6 rebounds and 1 block in 26 regular-season games, including 19 starts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/pelicans/news/2018-pelicans-playoff-profile-emeka-okafor|title=2018 Pelicans Playoff Profile: Emeka Okafor|author=Jim Eichenhofer|work=NBA.com|date=April 16, 2018|accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref><ref name=undefeated/>  Okafor was waived by the Pelicans on September 19, 2018, just prior to the start of training camp.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pelicans Waive Emeka Okafor |url=https://www.nba.com/pelicans/pelicans-waive-emeka-okafor |website=NBA.com |accessdate=September 19, 2018 |date=September 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOkafor signed with the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] on September 21, 2018,<ref>{{cite web|title=Team Announces 2018 Training Camp Roster|url=https://www.nba.com/sixers/team-announces-2018-training-camp-roster|website=NBA.com|accessdate=September 21, 2018|date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> before being waived on October 13.<ref>{{cite web|title=Team Waives Three Players, Roster Stands at 17|url=https://www.nba.com/sixers/news/team-waives-three-players-roster-stands-17|website=NBA.com|accessdate=October 14, 2018|date=October 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Ulsan Hyundai Mobis Phoebus (2019\u2013present)===\nOn November 22, 2019, [[Ulsan Hyundai Mobis Phoebus]] was reported that they had added Okafor to their roster.<ref>{{cite web|title=\uc18d\ucd08\uc5d0 \uc654\ub358 \ud6c8\ub828\uc0c1\ub300 \uc624\uce74\ud3ec, \ubaa8\ube44\uc2a4 \uc720\ub2c8\ud3fc \ub2e4\uc2dc \uc785\ub294\ub2e4|language=KO|url=https://sports.news.naver.com/news.nhn?oid=065&aid=0000192790|date=November 22, 2019|website=naver.com|accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref> Okafor made his debut for the \n[[Ulsan Hyundai Mobis Phoebus]] on December 4, 2019, coming off from bench with a double-double of eleven points and twelve rebounds plus two assists and two blocks in a 60\u201365 loss to the [[Anyang KGC]].<ref>{{cite web|title=\uc6b8\uc0b0 \ud604\ub300\ubaa8\ube44\uc2a4\ud53c\ubc84\uc2a4 VS KGC\uc778\uc0bc\uacf5\uc0ac|language=KO|url=http://www.mobisphoebus.co.kr/game/31100_game-calendar.asp?play_date=2019-12-06|date=December 6, 2019|website=mobisphoebus.co.kr|accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Regular Season Round 15: Anyang KGC - Mobis Phoebus 65-60|url=https://www.eurobasket.com/boxScores/South%20Korea/2019/1206_1981_1221.asp|date=December 6, 2019|website=eurobasket.com|accessdate=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==NBA career statistics==\n\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===Regular season===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2004}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2004\u201305 Charlotte Bobcats season|Charlotte]]\n| 73 || 73 || '''35.6''' || .447 || .000 || .609 || 10.9 || .9 || .8 || 1.7 || '''15.1'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2005}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2005\u201306 Charlotte Bobcats season|Charlotte]]\n| 26 || 25 || 33.6 || .415 || \u2014 || .656 || 10.0 || '''1.2''' || .8 || 1.9 || 13.2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2006}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2006\u201307 Charlotte Bobcats season|Charlotte]]\n| 67 || 65 || 34.8 || .532 || \u2014 || .593 || '''11.3''' || '''1.2''' || '''.9''' || '''2.6''' || 14.4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2007}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2007\u201308 Charlotte Bobcats season|Charlotte]]\n| '''82''' || '''82''' || 33.1 || .535 || \u2014 || .570 || 10.7 || .9 || .8 || 1.7 || 13.8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2008}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2008\u201309 Charlotte Bobcats season|Charlotte]]\n| '''82''' || 81 || 32.8 || .561 || \u2014 || .593 || 10.1 || .6 || .6 || 1.7 || 13.2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2009}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2009\u201310 New Orleans Hornets season|New Orleans]]\n| '''82''' || '''82''' || 28.9 || .530 || \u2014 || .562 || 9.0 || .7 || .7 || 1.5 || 10.4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2010}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2010\u201311 New Orleans Hornets season|New Orleans]]\n| 72 || 72 || 31.8 || '''.573''' || .000 || .562 || 9.5 || .6 || .6 || 1.8 || 10.3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2011}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2011\u201312 New Orleans Hornets season|New Orleans]]\n| 27 ||