{"title_page": "Annaamalai", "text_new": "{{short description|1992 film by Suresh Krissna}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Annaamalai\n| image          = Annaamalai poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Suresh Krissna]]\n| producer       = Rajam Balachander<br />Puspha Kandasamy\n| screenplay     = Suresh Krissna<br />[[Shanmugasundaram]]\n| based_on       = {{based on|''[[Khudgarz]]''}}\n| starring       = [[Rajinikanth]]<br />[[Khushbu Sundar|Kushboo]]<br />[[Sarath Babu]]\n| music          = [[Deva (composer)|Deva]]\n| cinematography = P. S. Prakash\n| editing        = Ganesh\u2013Kumar\n| studio         = [[Kavithalayaa Productions]]\n| released       = {{film date|1992|6|27|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 164 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n}}\n\n'''''Annaamalai''''' (also spelt '''''Annamalai'''''; {{IPA-ta|a\u0273\u0273a\u02d0mal\u032aa\u026a\u032f|pron}}) is a 1992 Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil]]-language [[action drama film]] directed by [[Suresh Krissna]] and produced by [[Kavithalayaa Productions]]. A remake of the 1987 [[Hindi]] film ''[[Khudgarz]]'', itself based on [[Jeffrey Archer]]'s novel ''[[Kane and Abel (novel)|Kane and Abel]]'', it stars [[Rajinikanth]], [[Khushbu Sundar|Kushboo]] and [[Sarath Babu]] with [[Radha Ravi]], [[Nizhalgal Ravi]] and [[Manorama (Tamil actress)|Manorama]] in supporting roles. The film revolves around Annaamalai, a poor milkman, and Ashok, the son of a rich businessman, who have been friends since childhood, a friendship opposed by Ashok's father who attempts to create a rift between the two.\n\n''Annaamalai'' was launched with director [[Vasanth]], who later opted out due to personal reasons. Suresh Krissna replaced him as director, and also contributed to the screenplay while Shanmugasundaram wrote the dialogues. [[Principal photography]] of the film began in March 1992 and the entire filming process lasted 45 working days. The score and soundtrack were composed by [[Deva (composer)|Deva]] and lyrics for all songs were written by [[Vairamuthu]]. The cinematography was handled by P. S. Prakash and editing by the duo Ganesh\u2013Kumar.\n\n''Annaamalai'' was released on 27 June 1992. The film became a box-office success, running for 175 days in theatres and was the highest-grossing film in [[Tamil cinema]] until 1995 when the record was broken by ''[[Baashha]]''. It was remade in [[Telugu language|Telugu]] in 1993 as ''[[Kondapalli Raja]]'' and in [[Kannada]] in 2003 as ''[[Gokarna (film)|Gokarna]]''.\n\n== Plot ==\nAnnaamalai is a milkman, while Ashok is the owner of a five-star hotel in Chennai. They have been very close friends since their childhood. Ashok's father Gangadharan never liked his son's friendship with a poor milkman. Annaamalai is kind-hearted and innocent, and falls in love with Subbulakshmi, a college girl he eventually marries. Ashok too falls in love with a poor girl, Shanthi. Annaamalai arranges Ashok and Shanthi's wedding which angers Gangadharan as he thinks Shanthi lacks the status to become his daughter-in-law.\n\nAnnaamalai encounters a problem with a politician named Ekambaram following which Ekambaram understands Annaamalai's good nature. Annaamalai's small home along with a few cents of empty land is located in prime location, to which Annaamalai held sentimental values to, made Gangadharan pressure Ashok to buy so that they can construct a star hotel. Ashok is initially hesitant as he does not want to mix business and friendship, but later agrees. Annaamalai happily accepts and also agrees to give the land for free of cost emulating pure friendship. Ashok feels proud of Annaamalai and informs his father that Annaamalai has to be made a shareholder in the new hotel. Gangadharan agrees but decides to cheat Annaamalai and gets signature in empty papers.\n\nThe star hotel is constructed and Gangadharan plans to demolish Annaamalai's home which is located next to the hotel. Gangadharan and Ashok's cousin Sargunam forge documents and take control of Annaamalai's empty land. Annaamalai learns of this plan and picks up quarrel with Gangadharan. Ashok interrupts and he misunderstands Annaamalai without knowing the truth for fighting with Ashok's father. Ashok gets angry and demolishes Annaamalai's home which is in the remembrance of Annaamalai's father. In response, Annaamalai challenges that he will also become rich and take revenge on Ashok.\n\nEkambaram helps Annaamalai to secure funds. Annaamalai starts a small sweets business and, over the course of fifteen years, he becomes so rich and he also builds a star hotel in Chennai which becomes more popular than Ashok's hotel. Sargunam steals money from Ashok and knowing this, Ashok asks him to leave. Sargunam joins Annaamalai's hotel and also marries Annaamalai's sister, Kamala. Annaamalai wins Ashok and become the president of hotels association and Ashok also faces financial troubles. Annaamalai's daughter and Ashok's son love each other; Annamalai opposes this because of his hatred for Ashok. Annaamalai and Ashok appear for a public auction and the auction price keeps increasing. Ashok wins the auction for {{INRConvert|120|m|lk=no|year=1992}} despite Gangadharan asking him not to quote such a huge amount as this was a trick played by Annaamalai to increase the price.\n\nAshok has no money to pay for the auction and is forced to sell his bungalow to get money. Annaamalai purchases Ashok's bungalow, thereby winning the challenge made years ago. But Annaamalai gives the registration document to his mother Sivagami and asks her to handover to Ashok itself thinking about the old friendship in mind and he did not want to punish his friend. Ashok and Gangadharan realise their mistake and apologise to Sivagami knowing Annaamalai's kind heart. Annaamalai also gets to know that it was only Gangadharan and Sargunam who forged the documents and Ashok was unaware of his father's plans. Sargunam later hires an assassin to kill Ashok to usurp his wealth. But Annaamalai saves Ashok, kills the assassin and Sargunam seeks forgiveness. Annaamalai and Ashok reconcile and become best friends again, and fix their children's marriage.\n\n== Cast ==\n*[[Rajinikanth]] as Annaamalai\n*[[Khushbu Sundar|Kushboo]] as Subbulakshmi\n*[[Sarath Babu]] as Ashok\n*[[Rekha (South Indian actress)|Rekha]] as Shanthi<ref name=\"dinamalarnellai\" />\n*[[Radha Ravi]] as Gangadharan\n*[[Janagaraj]] as Panchachari (Panchu)\n*[[Nizhalgal Ravi]] as Sargunam{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=53}}\n*[[Tiger Prabhakar]] as Don<ref>{{cite news |last1=Raman |first1=Pratiba |title=Rajinikanth\u2019s Darbar trailer breakdown/review: How is it? Simply superstar! |url=https://newsable.asianetnews.com/entertainment/rajinikanth-trailer-breakdown-review-how-is-it-simply-superstar--q2m6ec |accessdate=22 January 2020 |work=[[Asianet News]] |date=16 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Vinu Chakravarthy]] as Ekambaram<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/man-who-found-silk-smitha-vinu-chakravarthy-reminded-us-classism-cinema-61116 |title=The man who found Silk Smitha: Vinu Chakravarthy reminded us of the classicism in cinema |last=Sundaram |first=Nandhu |date=28 April 2017 |work=[[The News Minute]] |access-date=7 September 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171216200648/http://www.thenewsminute.com/article/man-who-found-silk-smitha-vinu-chakravarthy-reminded-us-classism-cinema-61116 |archive-date=16 December 2017}}</ref>{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=71}}\n*[[Manorama (Tamil actress)|Manorama]] as Sivagami\n*[[Vaishnavi (Malayali actress)|Vaishnavi]] as Kamala, Annaamalai's sister{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=80}}\n*Vishnukanth as Junior Ashok credited as Master Vishnu\n*[[Karan (actor)|Karan]] as Deepak (uncredited), Ashok's son\n*Dakshayini as Priya (uncredited), Annaamalai's daughter<ref name=\"dinamalarnellai\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.dinamalarnellai.com/cinema/news/32208 |title=\u0b9a\u0bbe\u0ba4\u0ba9\u0bc8 \u0baa\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bbf\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4 \u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0bcd \u0baa\u0b9f\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd&nbsp;\u2013 306\u2013 \u0b8e\u0bb8\u0bcd.\u0b95\u0ba3\u0bc7\u0bb7\u0bcd |date=1 August 2017 |website=[[Dinamalar]] |location=Nellai |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190907154603/http://www.dinamalarnellai.com/cinema/news/32208 |archive-date=7 September 2019 |access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Development ===\nIn the first week of March 1992, the newspaper ''[[Dina Thanthi]]'' announced [[K. Balachander]]'s production house Kavithalayaa Productions' next film ''Annaamalai'', with [[Vasanth]] as director and [[Rajinikanth]] as lead actor.{{sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=7}} When the title of the film was announced as ''Annaamalai'', few people has misgivings about the title as it would create a negative connotation. Balachander and Rajinikanth had decided on the title and refused to change it.{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=15}} After completing work on ''[[Jaagruti]]'' on 8 March, [[Suresh Krissna]] left for Madras (now [[Chennai]]) the next morning; he wanted a break as he had not yet signed his next film. Upon arrival the same day, he was informed that Balachander, his mentor, was waiting for him. Krissna visited Balachander, who told him that Vasanth had left ''Annaamalai'', which was scheduled to begin filming in two days and its release date fixed for June. When asked if he would direct, Krissna received an advance of {{INRConvert|109|year=1992}} and accepted.{{sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|pp=8\u20139}} Vasanth has never expanded on why he left, saying it was only due to \"personal reasons\".{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=145}} [[Visu]] claims he was hired as the director before Vasanth, but due to some contradiction with Rajinikanth, he opted out.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_yb192cswUI |title=Rajini is very intelligent and grasps things quickly says Visu {{!}} Heartist |last=Bosskey |authorlink=Bosskey |date=17 June 2016 |website=[[YouTube]] |publisher=Bosskey TV |url-status=live |access-date=30 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of Krissna's arrival, the script was not complete; he met the film's screenwriter Shanmugasundaram, who narrated the main story: the \"friendship between a poor milkman and a rich man, with the former's house being a point of conflict\". Krissna realised there was still a lot of work to be done because reasons like \"why does his house mean so much to him, why does the rich man's father hate this milkman, what angers the hero so much that he goes against his rich friend\" had yet to be established. The story was based on the Hindi film ''[[Khudgarz]]'' (1987),<ref name=\"NoAnnamalaiNoBaashha\" /> which itself was based on [[Jeffrey Archer]]'s novel ''[[Kane and Abel (novel)|Kane and Abel]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/news/jeffrey-archer-accuses-bollywood-of-stealing-his-bestselling-storylines-10085842.html |title=Jeffrey Archer accuses Bollywood of stealing his bestselling |last=Sherwin |first=Adam |date=4 March 2015 |work=[[The Independent]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191101162127/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/news/jeffrey-archer-accuses-bollywood-of-stealing-his-bestselling-storylines-10085842.html |archive-date=1 November 2019 |access-date=1 November 2019}}</ref> Unlike ''Khudgarz'', where the rich man was the main character, Rajinikanth's character, the poor man, was made the main character. When Krissna asked Shanmugasundaram about the \"incomplete pockets\" in the story, Shanmugasundaram replied that it could all be developed over the course of production.<ref name=\"NoAnnamalaiNoBaashha\" /> Shanmugasundaram had been hired at Rajinikanth's suggestion.{{sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=10}}\n\nWhen Krissna met Rajinikanth, he told him that there was a substantial amount of work to be done in the script, but liked the plot.{{sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|pp=10\u201311}}{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=146}} Shortly before the beginning of principal photography, which was scheduled to begin on 11 March and continue its first schedule for ten days,{{sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=11}} only the main cast&nbsp;\u2013 Rajinikanth as the title character, [[Khushbu Sundar|Khushbu]] as his love interest and [[Sarath Babu]] as his friend Ashok&nbsp;\u2013 had been finalised.<ref name=\"NoAnnamalaiNoBaashha\" />{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=149}} Khushbu's character initially had the same name as her, but this was later changed to Subbulakshmi alias \"Subbu\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vikatan.com/oddities/celebrity/16969--2 |title=\u0bb5\u0bbf\u0b95\u0b9f\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bc7\u0b9f\u0bc8: \u0b95\u0bc1\u0bb7\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1 |date=14 March 2012 |website=[[Ananda Vikatan]] |language=ta |trans-title=Vikatan Desk: Khushbu |url-status=live |access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref> Since the script was not complete, there was no proper shooting schedule, and [[Manorama (Tamil actress)|Manorama]] was initially unavailable. But after another film she had signed got cancelled, she was cast in ''Annaamalai'' as the title character's mother Sivagami.<ref name=\"NoAnnamalaiNoBaashha\" /><ref name=\"IE review\" /> [[Radha Ravi]] was cast as Ashok's father Gangadharan.<ref name=\"IE review\" /> He was not interested in playing an elderly character, but agreed to appear in ''Annaamalai'' at Rajinikanth's insistence.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/refrains-old-and-new/article2973933.ece |title=Refrains, old and new |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |date=8 March 2012 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=17 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140417115209/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/refrains-old-and-new/article2973933.ece |archive-date=17 April 2014}}</ref> Pre-production works such as casting and location hunting took place on the day before shooting began.{{sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=14}}{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=146}} Balachander's wife Rajam and their daughter Pushpa Kandhaswamy received the producer credit.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.primevideo.com/detail/0G9H0HF3Q383AVXDYPQ7JURJHX |title=Annamalai |website=[[Prime Video]] |publisher=[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |access-date=16 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\n''Annaamalai'' was launched at AVM Studios at the venue of Pillaiyar temple.{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=15}} [[Principal photography]] began on 11 March 1992.<ref name=\"NoAnnamalaiNoBaashha\" /> After the film's [[muhurat shot]], the first scene to be filmed was a comedy scene where Annaamalai would save Ashok, who has been brought to court for a minor offence. Krissna removed the scene from the final cut as he felt it had no bearing on the script.{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|pp=17\u201318}}\n\nThe scene where Annaamalai enters a ladies' hostel and gets terrified by a snake was shot at Chakra House, Alwarpet.{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|page=19}} A snake was brought specially for the scene. The owner of the snake earlier worked in previous films of Rajinikanth. Suresh asked his assistants Nagappan and [[K. Natraj]] to check the details about the snake charmer. Krissna recalled that he covered his nervousness with his smile. Krissna told cinematographer P. S. Prakash to use zoom lens so that he could adjust a camera according to the situation. After the scene was finished, the members of the crew enjoyed the shot. Krissna congratulated Rajinikanth and asked him how he performed it so well and if it was planned, and Rajinikanth replied it was not planned; expressions in the scene were a result of his fear. In the same scene, Shanmugasundaram came with initial dialogues to convey Annaamalai's fear. Krissna felt that dialogues were redundant in such situation. Rajinikanth insisted to keep ''Kadavule Kadavule'' (Oh God! Oh God!) as the dialogue. Krissna agreed to keep the dialogue as it went well into the situation of the scene.{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|pp=19\u201324}} According to Krissna, nobody on set realised that the snake's mouth was not stitched; it was only after filming ended for that day that the director came to realise that Rajinikanth's life was at risk the entire time.{{sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|pp=25\u201326}}\n\nKrissna wanted the picturisation of \"Vanthenda Paalkaaran\" to be vibrant and colourful stating that he got inspired from the Hindi songs of [[Amitabh Bachchan]]. The scene where Annaamalai shows his face to the camera was extended in slow motion by Krissna as fans would feel as if he was looking towards the audience. The song was choreographed by [[Prabhu Deva]].{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|pp=31\u201334}} The title song \"Annaamalai\" where the title character and Subbu appear in periodic costumes was shot at Fern Hill Palace Hotel while the matching shots were shot at Sivaji Gardens. Krissna shot the song sequence in a technique where the lip sync is perfect while the dance movements being fast revealing that he got inspired from the song \"Mamavukku Koduma\" from ''[[Punnagai Mannan]]'' (1986).{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|pp=35\u201337}} The scene where Annaamalai beats up Sargunam in a one-sided fight was filmed at [[Egmore#Various buildings|Hotel Ambassador Pallava]].{{sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=81}} Filming was completed in 45 working days.{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=146}}\n\n=== Post-production ===\n[[File:Super Star Rajni.gif|thumb|The \"Super Star\" graphic title card]]\n''Annaamalai'' was edited by the duo Ganesh\u2013Kumar.{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=68}} It was the first film to feature the introductory \"Super Star\" graphic title card, where the words 'SUPER' and 'STAR' form in blue dots on the screen followed by R-A-J-N-I in gold, set to the sound of laser beams while the word \"Hey!\" plays in [[Loop (music)|loop]] in the background.<ref name=\"SuperStarTitle\" />{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=148}} This idea was conceived by Krissna, who was inspired by the opening [[gun barrel sequence]] in the [[Production of the James Bond films|James Bond films]], and felt that Rajinikanth, who was becoming a phenomenon, \"warranted a unique logo to go with his name\".{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=89}}\n\nRajinikanth initially objected to the inclusion of the Super Star title card as he felt it was \"brazen self-aggrandisement\" and \"embarrassing\",{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=90}} but Krissna convinced him, saying it would generate large applause.{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|pp=148\u2013149}} Balachander supported Krissna, and asked Rajinikanth, \"What is wrong in Suresh's idea Rajini? People are clapping for your name. It is a great idea and let's go for it\", after which Rajinikanth relented.<ref name=\"SureshKrissnaBehindwoods\" /> The final cut of the film was initially {{convert|14950|feet|metres}}, at a time when the length of Tamil films was restricted to {{convert|14500|feet|metres}}, equal to two hours and forty-five minutes. With the removal of the courtroom scene, the film's final length was reduced by {{convert|450|feet|metres}}.{{sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|pp=17\u201318}}\n\n== Music ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Annaamalai\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Deva (composer)|Deva]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1992\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Lahari Music]]\n| producer   = \n| prev_title = [[Vaigasi Poranthachu]]\n| prev_year  = 1991\n| next_title = [[Suriyan]]\n| next_year  = 1992\n}}\n\nThe soundtrack was composed by [[Deva (composer)|Deva]], with lyrics by [[Vairamuthu]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.raaga.com/channels/tamil/moviedetail.asp?mid=T0001968 |title=Annamalai (1992) |website=[[Raaga.com]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117024856/http://www.raaga.com/channels/tamil/moviedetail.asp?mid=T0001968 |archive-date=17 January 2012 |access-date=8 March 2012}}</ref> It was released under the [[Lahari Music|Lahari]] label.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.jiosaavn.com/album/annamalai/1sm6jY5EXz8_ |title=Annamalai |website=[[JioSaavn]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716035202/https://www.jiosaavn.com/album/annamalai/1sm6jY5EXz8_ |archive-date=16 July 2019 |access-date=16 July 2019}}</ref> ''Annaamalai'' marked Deva's first collaboration with Rajinikanth. Balachander chose him as composer due to a misunderstanding with his usual composer [[Ilaiyaraaja]]. Rajinikanth and Krissna were initially worried with the choice of Deva.{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|pp=29\u201330}} When Krissna met Deva, he had already composed the song \"Annaamalai Annaamalai\" when Vasanth was the director.{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|page=30}} The song is set in the [[Carnatic raga]] known as [[Mohanam]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/music/music-composer-deva-talks-about-tweaking-ragas-and-understanding-film-music-in-his-journey-from-composer-to-singer/article19316698.ece |title=Composer Deva: the monarch of Gaana music |last=Saravanan |first=T. |date=20 July 2017 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=6 June 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181030035929/https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/music/music-composer-deva-talks-about-tweaking-ragas-and-understanding-film-music-in-his-journey-from-composer-to-singer/article19316698.ece |archive-date=30 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n\"Vanthenda Paalkaaran\" was inspired by a Kannada poem which Rajinikanth had suggested; the poem talked about cows as deities, useful to humans in many ways. Vairamuthu grasped the core of the poem and embellished it further, adding an element of contrast between the ever-giving cow and selfish humans who only take from other beings. He also inserted a few ingenious words to boost Rajinikanth's image as a \"mass hero\" of the Tamils, such as \"Ennai Vaazha Vaithadhu Tamizh Paalu\" (It is the milk of love from you Tamils that has given me life).{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|pp=31\u201332}} The song's tune is based on the [[Marathi language|Marathi]] folk song \"Mee Dolkar Daryacha Raja\" (1969).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.filmcompanion.in/the-kannada-and-marathi-roots-of-rajinikanths-first-hero-introduction-song/ |title=The Kannada And Marathi Roots Of Rajinikanth's First Hero Introduction Song |last=Srinivasan |first=Karthik |date=20 November 2018 |website=[[Film Companion]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120104341/https://www.filmcompanion.in/the-kannada-and-marathi-roots-of-rajinikanths-first-hero-introduction-song/# |archive-date=20 November 2018 |access-date=20 November 2018}}</ref> The theme song, which does not appear on the soundtrack and plays during the Super Star graphic title card,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://scroll.in/reel/883765/how-tamil-composer-deva-churned-out-the-hits-a-film-song-should-immediately-register-with-people |title=How Tamil composer Deva rolled out the hits: \u2018A film song should immediately register with people\u2019 |last=Yamunan |first=Sruthisagar |date=24 June 2018 |website=[[Scroll.in]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190906054743/https://scroll.in/reel/883765/how-tamil-composer-deva-churned-out-the-hits-a-film-song-should-immediately-register-with-people |archive-date=6 September 2019 |access-date=6 September 2019}}</ref> was inspired by the [[James Bond Theme]].<ref name=\"NoAnnamalaiNoBaashha\" />\n{{Track listing\n| headline      = \n| extra_column  = Singer(s)\n| total_length  = \n| title1        = Vanthenda Paalkaran\n| extra1        = [[S. P. Balasubrahmanyam]]\n| length1       = 5:06\n| title2        = Annaamalai Annaamalai\n| extra2        = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam, [[K. S. Chithra]]\n| length2       = 4:58\n| title3        = Kondayil Thaazham Poo\n| extra3        = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam, K. S. Chithra\n| length3       = 4:41\n| title4        = Vetri Nichayam\n| extra4        = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam\n| length4       = 4:14\n| title5        = Oru Pen Pura\n| extra5        = [[K. J. Yesudas]]\n| length5       = 5:13\n| title6        = Rekkai Katti Parakudhu\n| extra6        = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam, K. S. Chithra\n| length6       = 4:23\n}}\n\n== Release ==\n''Annaamalai'' was released on 27 June 1992.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.google.co.in/newspapers?nid=P9oYG7HA76QC&dat=19920627&printsec=frontpage&hl=en |title=Annaamalai |date=27 June 1992 |work=[[The Indian Express]] |page=3}}</ref> Its opening was threatened since the new government of [[J. Jayalalithaa]] implemented a new rule where posters of films were prohibited in Madras. Nevertheless, according to Krissna, the lack of promos only increased the hype and worked to the film's advantage;{{sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=76}}\n\n== Reception ==\nIn a review dated 3 July, Lalitha Dileep of ''[[The Indian Express]]'' said, \"the film combines good screenplay, proficient direction and first rate acting. The end result is both entertaining and engrossing\". She said the metamorphosis of Annaamalai from a simpleton to a wealthy man was \"done in a plausible manner and with great cinematic finesse\", praised the editing, the cinematography, the music and lyrics, concluding, \"[''Annaamalai''] is enjoyable and touching.\"<ref name=\"IE review\" /> K. Vijiyan of ''[[New Straits Times]]'' wrote on 11 July, \"[''Annaamalai''] will be hit with Rajni's admirers but a disappointment for Balachander's discerning fans who are looking for a story with a difference\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=PqRUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OpADAAAAIBAJ&pg=2717%2C247623 |title=Revenge storyline getting too stale |last=Vijiyan |first=K. |date=11 July 1992 |work=[[New Straits Times]] |page=13}}</ref> A special screening was held for actor [[Sivaji Ganesan]] who told Krissna, \"In my heyday, the camera remained steady while I would move up and down to make an impact as a hero, but you've limited [Rajinikanth's] movements and made the camera whirl around. The dynamism of the shots have helped project heroism better [...] You've showcased another dimension of [Rajinikanth]. The film's plus is its making.\"{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|page=93}}\n\nThe film completed a 175-day run at the box office.{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|page=69}} It was the highest-grossing film in [[Tamil cinema]] until 1995 when the record was broken by ''[[Baashha]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/regional/will-kabali-be-rajinikanths-most-revered-film-here-are-his-top-10-roles-1434235 |title=Will Kabali be Rajinikanth's Most Revered Film? Here Are His Top 10 Roles |last=Goyal |first=Divya |date=22 July 2016 |website=[[NDTV]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303160854/http://movies.ndtv.com/regional/will-kabali-be-rajinikanths-most-revered-film-here-are-his-top-10-roles-1434235 |archive-date=3 March 2018 |access-date=3 March 2018}}</ref> The collections of ''Annaamalai'' sent tremors everywhere. ''Annaamalai'' exceeded normal regional collections making the film producers all over India sit up and take notice. With ''Annaamalai'', Rajinikanth's range increased and made him the highest-paid actor in India till now. Tamil Manila Congress and DMK ally prioritised 'Annaamalai Cycle', and won the 1996 elections by a huge margin.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/vasans-new-party-to-retain-tmc-as-brand-name/article6647144.ece |title=Vasan's new party to retain TMC as 'brand name' |last=Kolappan |first=B. |date=30 November 2014 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=17 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205163446/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/vasans-new-party-to-retain-tmc-as-brand-name/article6647144.ece |archive-date=5 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/only-rajini-can/articleshow/756523.cms |title=Only Rajini can |last=Govardan |first=D. |date=10 December 2006 |work=[[The Economic Times]] |access-date=15 July 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190715114927/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/only-rajini-can/articleshow/756523.cms |archive-date=15 July 2019}}</ref> For his performance, Rajinikanth won the Ambika Award for Best Actor.{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=269}} \n\n== Remakes ==\n''Annaamalai'' was remade into [[Telugu language|Telugu]] in 1993 as ''[[Kondapalli Raja]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.telugucinema.com/c/publish/stars/interview_ravirajapinishetty2010_3.php |title=Interview: Ravi Raja Pinisetty |last=Sri |date=15 July 2010 |website=Telugucinema.com |page=3 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101231093534/http://www.telugucinema.com/c/publish/stars/interview_ravirajapinishetty2010_3.php |archive-date=31 December 2010 |access-date=8 March 2012}}</ref> and into [[Kannada]] in 2003 as ''[[Gokarna (film)|Gokarna]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/2004/01/04/stories/2004010408720500.htm |title=2003, a flop for Kannada cinema |last=Venkatasubba Rao |first=K. N. |date=4 January 2004 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=28 February 2018 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228162004/http://www.thehindu.com/2004/01/04/stories/2004010408720500.htm |archive-date=28 February 2018}}</ref> Despite its Telugu remake, the film was also dubbed in that language as ''Birla Ramudu''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.moviefone.com/movie/birla-ramudu/zvRxXAJ6wd3GkO0qJ4smr5/main/ |title=Birla Ramudu (1992) |website=[[Moviefone]] |language=en |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191023041359/https://www.moviefone.com/movie/birla-ramudu/zvRxXAJ6wd3GkO0qJ4smr5/main/ |archive-date=23 October 2019 |access-date=23 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\n<!-- http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/2017/dec/20/debunking-movie-myths-the-annamalai-style-of-blowing-up-cars-1732814.html -->\n''Annaamalai'' set a trend in Tamil cinema: a \"mass introduction song for a hero\".<ref name=\"SureshKrissnaBehindwoods\" /> Additionally, the \"Super Star\" graphic title card continued to feature in many of Rajinikanth's later films like ''[[Veera (1994 film)|Veera]]'' (1994), ''Baashha'' and ''[[Muthu (1995 film)|Muthu]]'' (1995).<ref name=\"SuperStarTitle\" /> [[Jai (actor)|Jai]] stated that his character from ''[[Engaeyum Eppothum]]'' (2011) \"was almost modelled on the lines of Rajini Sir in the first half of [''Annaamalai'']\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/hitman/article5276396.ece |title=Hit-man |last=Rao |first=Subha J |date=27 October 2013 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=17 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140830183553/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/hitman/article5276396.ece |archive-date=30 August 2014}}</ref> Suresh Krishna directed ''[[Arumugam (film)|Aarumugam]]'' in 2009 which critics compared with ''Annaamalai'' due to its similar plot and characterisations.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/true-to-formula/article3021972.ece |title=True to formula |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |date=2 October 2009 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=17 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181030035737/https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/true-to-formula/article3021972.ece# |archive-date=30 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe dialogue \"Naan Solradaiyum Seiven, Soladadeiyum Seiven\" (I'll do what I say, I'll also do what I don't say) attained popularity.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/regional-movies/watch-all-the-rajini-fans-thalaiva-s-five-iconic-dialogues/story-0dFbrhMGiFejgRQxs9oZeL.html |title=WATCH: All the Rajini fans... Thalaiva\u2019s five iconic dialogues |last=Mishra |first=Nivedita |date=12 December 2014 |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |access-date=28 February 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228223156/https://www.hindustantimes.com/regional-movies/watch-all-the-rajini-fans-thalaiva-s-five-iconic-dialogues/story-0dFbrhMGiFejgRQxs9oZeL.html |archive-date=28 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe scenes from the film were parodied in ''[[Paarthale Paravasam]]'' (2001),<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Paarthale Paravasam |type=motion picture |language=ta |publisher=[[Kavithalayaa Productions]] |year=2001 |time=6:30 to 7:14 |time-caption=From}}</ref> ''[[Boss Engira Bhaskaran]]'' (2010),<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movie-reviews/Boss-Engira-Bhaskaran/movie-review/6547029.cms |title=Boss Engira Bhaskaran Movie Review |last=Ravi |first=Bhama Devi |date=10 September 2010 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=17 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150731015349/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movie-reviews/Boss-Engira-Bhaskaran/movie-review/6547029.cms |archive-date=31 July 2015}}</ref> and ''[[Thamizh Padam]]'' (2010).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/tamil-padam-review-tamil-pclx0Wibgbecd.html |title=Tamil Padam |date=29 January 2010 |website=[[Sify]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228162913/http://www.sify.com/movies/tamil-padam-review-tamil-pclx0Wibgbecd.html |archive-date=28 February 2018 |access-date=28 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"SureshKrissnaBehindwoods\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-cinema-news-16/director-suresh-krissna-on-25-years-of-rajinis-film-annamalai.html |title=Rajini was stopped at the entrance of Poes Garden |last=Bhavanishankar |first=Jyothsna |date=27 June 2017 |website=Behindwoods |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6xYzdCvFo?url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-cinema-news-16/director-suresh-krissna-on-25-years-of-rajinis-film-annamalai.html |archive-date=28 February 2018 |access-date=28 February 2018}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"SuperStarTitle\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.filmcompanion.in/a-superstar-career-through-titles-rajinikanth-aboorva-raagangal-to-2-0/ |title=A Superstar Career Through Titles |last=Shivakumar |first=Vivek |date=11 December 2018 |website=[[Film Companion]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714155517/https://www.filmcompanion.in/a-superstar-career-through-titles-rajinikanth-aboorva-raagangal-to-2-0/ |archive-date=14 July 2019 |access-date=15 July 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"NoAnnamalaiNoBaashha\">{{Cite news |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/without-annamalai-there-wouldnt-be-baashha/articleshow/59322761.cms |title=Without Annamalai, there wouldn't be Baashha |last=Krissna |first=Suresh |date=27 June 2017 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=28 February 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228223001/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/without-annamalai-there-wouldnt-be-baashha/articleshow/59322761.cms |archive-date=28 February 2018 |last2=Suganth |first2=M. |author-link=Suresh Krissna}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"IE review\">{{Cite news |url=https://news.google.co.in/newspapers?nid=P9oYG7HA76QC&dat=19920703&printsec=frontpage&hl=en |title=Soul-mates forever |last=Dileep |first=Lalitha |date=3 July 1992 |work=[[The Indian Express]] |page=7}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{Cite book |title=My Days with Baasha |last=Krissna |first=Suresh |last2=Rangarajan |first2=Malathi |publisher=Westland Ltd. |year=2012 |isbn=978-93-8162-629-0 |ref=harv |author-link=Suresh Krissna}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Rajinikanth: The Definitive Biography |title-link=Rajinikanth: The Definitive Biography |last=Ramachandran |first=Naman |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |year=2014 |isbn=978-81-8475-796-5 |ref=harv |author-link=Naman Ramachandran |orig-year=2012}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote|Annamalai}}\n* {{IMDb title|0139859}}\n\n{{Kavithalaya Productions}}\n{{Suresh Krissna}}\n\n[[Category:1990s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:1990s action drama films]]\n[[Category:1990s buddy films]]\n[[Category:1992 films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Suresh Krissna]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Deva (composer)]]\n[[Category:Indian action drama films]]\n[[Category:Indian buddy films]]\n[[Category:Indian films about revenge]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Tamil remakes of Hindi films]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1992 film by Suresh Krissna}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Annaamalai\n| image          = Annaamalai poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Suresh Krissna]]\n| producer       = Rajam Balachander<br />Puspha Kandasamy\n| screenplay     = Suresh Krissna<br />[[Shanmugasundaram]]\n| based_on       = {{based on|''[[Khudgarz]]''}}\n| starring       = [[Rajinikanth]]<br />[[Khushbu Sundar|Kushboo]]<br />[[Sarath Babu]]\n| music          = [[Deva (composer)|Deva]]\n| cinematography = P. S. Prakash\n| editing        = Ganesh\u2013Kumar\n| studio         = [[Kavithalayaa Productions]]\n| released       = {{film date|1992|6|27|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 164 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n}}\n\n'''''Annaamalai''''' (also spelt '''''Annamalai'''''; {{IPA-ta|a\u0273\u0273a\u02d0mal\u032aa\u026a\u032f|pron}}) is a 1992 Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil]]-language [[action drama film]] directed by [[Suresh Krissna]] and produced by [[Kavithalayaa Productions]]. A remake of the 1987 [[Hindi]] film ''[[Khudgarz]]'', itself based on [[Jeffrey Archer]]'s novel ''[[Kane and Abel (novel)|Kane and Abel]]'', it stars [[Rajinikanth]], [[Khushbu Sundar|Kushboo]] and [[Sarath Babu]] with [[Radha Ravi]], [[Nizhalgal Ravi]] and [[Manorama (Tamil actress)|Manorama]] in supporting roles. The film revolves around Annaamalai, a poor milkman, and Ashok, the son of a rich businessman, who have been friends since childhood, a friendship opposed by Ashok's father who attempts to create a rift between the two.\n\n''Annaamalai'' was launched with director [[Vasanth]], who later opted out due to personal reasons. Suresh Krissna replaced him as director, and also contributed to the screenplay while Shanmugasundaram wrote the dialogues. [[Principal photography]] of the film began in March 1992 and the entire filming process lasted 45 working days. The score and soundtrack were composed by [[Deva (composer)|Deva]] and lyrics for all songs were written by [[Vairamuthu]]. The cinematography was handled by P. S. Prakash and editing by the duo Ganesh\u2013Kumar.\n\n''Annaamalai'' was released on 27 June 1992. The film became a box-office success, running for 175 days in theatres and was the highest-grossing film in [[Tamil cinema]] until 1995 when the record was broken by ''[[Baashha]]''. It was remade in [[Telugu language|Telugu]] in 1993 as ''[[Kondapalli Raja]]'' and in [[Kannada]] in 2003 as ''[[Gokarna (film)|Gokarna]]''.\n\n== Plot ==\nAnnaamalai is a milkman, while Ashok is the owner of a five-star hotel in Chennai. They have been very close friends since their childhood. Ashok's father Gangadharan never liked his son's friendship with a poor milkman. Annaamalai is kind-hearted and innocent, and falls in love with Subbulakshmi, a college girl he eventually marries. Ashok too falls in love with a poor girl, Shanthi. Annaamalai arranges Ashok and Shanthi's wedding which angers Gangadharan as he thinks Shanthi does not have the status to become his daughter-in-law.\n\nAnnaamalai encounters a problem with a politician named Ekambaram following which Ekambaram understands Annaamalai's good nature. Annaamalai's small home along with a few cents of empty land is located in prime location, to which Annaamalai held sentimental values to, made Gangadharan pressurise Ashok to buy so that they can construct a star hotel. Ashok is initially hesitant as he does not want to mix business and friendship, but later agrees. Annaamalai happily accepts and also agrees to give the land for free of cost emulating pure friendship. Ashok feels proud of Annaamalai and informs his father that Annaamalai has to be made a shareholder in the new hotel. Gangadharan agrees but decides to cheat Annaamalai and gets signature in empty papers.\n\nThe star hotel is constructed and Gangadharan plans to demolish Annaamalai's home which is located next to the hotel. Gangadharan and Ashok's cousin Sargunam forge documents and take control of Annaamalai's empty land. Annaamalai learns of this plan and picks up quarrel with Gangadharan. Ashok interrupts and he misunderstands Annaamalai without knowing the truth for fighting with Ashok's father. Ashok gets angry and demolishes Annaamalai's home which is in the remembrance of Annaamalai's father. In response, Annaamalai challenges that he will also become rich and take revenge on Ashok.\n\nEkambaram helps Annaamalai to secure funds. Annaamalai starts a small sweets business and, over the course of fifteen years, he becomes so rich and he also builds a star hotel in Chennai which becomes more popular than Ashok's hotel. Sargunam steals money from Ashok and knowing this, Ashok asks him to leave. Sargunam joins Annaamalai's hotel and also gets married to Annaamalai's sister, Kamala. Annaamalai wins Ashok and become the president of hotels association and Ashok also faces financial troubles. Annaamalai's daughter and Ashok's son love each other; Annamalai opposes this because of his hatred for Ashok. Annaamalai and Ashok appear for a public auction and the auction price keeps increasing. Ashok wins the auction for {{INRConvert|120|m|lk=no|year=1992}} despite Gangadharan asking him not to quote such a huge amount as this was a trick played by Annaamalai to increase the price.\n\nAshok has no money to pay for the auction and is forced to sell his bungalow to get money. Annaamalai purchases Ashok's bungalow, thereby winning the challenge made years ago. But Annaamalai gives the registration document to his mother Sivagami and asks her to handover to Ashok itself thinking about the old friendship in mind and he did not want to punish his friend. Ashok and Gangadharan realise their mistake and apologise to Sivagami knowing Annaamalai's kind heart. Annaamalai also gets to know that it was only Gangadharan and Sargunam who forged the documents and Ashok was unaware of his father's plans. Sargunam later hires an assassin to kill Ashok to usurp his wealth. But Annaamalai saves Ashok, kills the assassin and Sargunam seeks forgiveness. Annaamalai and Ashok reconcile and become best friends again, and fix their children's marriage.\n\n== Cast ==\n*[[Rajinikanth]] as Annaamalai\n*[[Khushbu Sundar|Kushboo]] as Subbulakshmi\n*[[Sarath Babu]] as Ashok\n*[[Rekha (South Indian actress)|Rekha]] as Shanthi<ref name=\"dinamalarnellai\" />\n*[[Radha Ravi]] as Gangadharan\n*[[Janagaraj]] as Panchachari (Panchu)\n*[[Nizhalgal Ravi]] as Sargunam{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=53}}\n*[[Tiger Prabhakar]] as Don<ref>{{cite news |last1=Raman |first1=Pratiba |title=Rajinikanth\u2019s Darbar trailer breakdown/review: How is it? Simply superstar! |url=https://newsable.asianetnews.com/entertainment/rajinikanth-trailer-breakdown-review-how-is-it-simply-superstar--q2m6ec |accessdate=22 January 2020 |work=[[Asianet News]] |date=16 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Vinu Chakravarthy]] as Ekambaram<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/man-who-found-silk-smitha-vinu-chakravarthy-reminded-us-classism-cinema-61116 |title=The man who found Silk Smitha: Vinu Chakravarthy reminded us of the classicism in cinema |last=Sundaram |first=Nandhu |date=28 April 2017 |work=[[The News Minute]] |access-date=7 September 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171216200648/http://www.thenewsminute.com/article/man-who-found-silk-smitha-vinu-chakravarthy-reminded-us-classism-cinema-61116 |archive-date=16 December 2017}}</ref>{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=71}}\n*[[Manorama (Tamil actress)|Manorama]] as Sivagami\n*[[Vaishnavi (Malayali actress)|Vaishnavi]] as Kamala, Annaamalai's sister{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=80}}\n* Vishnukanth as Junior Ashok credited as Master Vishnu\n\nAdditionally, [[Karan (actor)|Karan]] appears as Ashok's son Deepak, and Dakshayini as Annaamalai's daughter Priya, both uncredited.<ref name=\"dinamalarnellai\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.dinamalarnellai.com/cinema/news/32208 |title=\u0b9a\u0bbe\u0ba4\u0ba9\u0bc8 \u0baa\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bbf\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4 \u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0bcd \u0baa\u0b9f\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd&nbsp;\u2013 306\u2013 \u0b8e\u0bb8\u0bcd.\u0b95\u0ba3\u0bc7\u0bb7\u0bcd |date=1 August 2017 |website=[[Dinamalar]] |location=Nellai |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190907154603/http://www.dinamalarnellai.com/cinema/news/32208 |archive-date=7 September 2019 |access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Development ===\nIn the first week of March 1992, the newspaper ''[[Dina Thanthi]]'' announced [[K. Balachander]]'s production house Kavithalayaa Productions' next film ''Annaamalai'', with [[Vasanth]] as director and [[Rajinikanth]] as lead actor.{{sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=7}} When the title of the film was announced as ''Annaamalai'', few people has misgivings about the title as it would create a negative connotation. Balachander and Rajinikanth had decided on the title and refused to change it.{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=15}} After completing work on ''[[Jaagruti]]'' on 8 March, [[Suresh Krissna]] left for Madras (now [[Chennai]]) the next morning; he wanted a break as he had not yet signed his next film. Upon arrival the same day, he was informed that Balachander, his mentor, was waiting for him. Krissna visited Balachander, who told him that Vasanth had left ''Annaamalai'', which was scheduled to begin filming in two days and its release date fixed for June. When asked if he would direct, Krissna received an advance of {{INRConvert|109|year=1992}} and accepted.{{sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|pp=8\u20139}} Vasanth has never expanded on why he left, saying it was only due to \"personal reasons\".{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=145}} [[Visu]] claims he was hired as the director before Vasanth, but due to some contradiction with Rajinikanth, he opted out.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_yb192cswUI |title=Rajini is very intelligent and grasps things quickly says Visu {{!}} Heartist |last=Bosskey |authorlink=Bosskey |date=17 June 2016 |website=[[YouTube]] |publisher=Bosskey TV |url-status=live |access-date=30 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of Krissna's arrival, the script was not complete; he met the film's screenwriter Shanmugasundaram, who narrated the main story: the \"friendship between a poor milkman and a rich man, with the former's house being a point of conflict\". Krissna realised there was still a lot of work to be done because reasons like \"why does his house mean so much to him, why does the rich man's father hate this milkman, what angers the hero so much that he goes against his rich friend\" had yet to be established. The story was based on the Hindi film ''[[Khudgarz]]'' (1987),<ref name=\"NoAnnamalaiNoBaashha\" /> which itself was based on [[Jeffrey Archer]]'s novel ''[[Kane and Abel (novel)|Kane and Abel]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/news/jeffrey-archer-accuses-bollywood-of-stealing-his-bestselling-storylines-10085842.html |title=Jeffrey Archer accuses Bollywood of stealing his bestselling |last=Sherwin |first=Adam |date=4 March 2015 |work=[[The Independent]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191101162127/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/news/jeffrey-archer-accuses-bollywood-of-stealing-his-bestselling-storylines-10085842.html |archive-date=1 November 2019 |access-date=1 November 2019}}</ref> Unlike ''Khudgarz'', where the rich man was the main character, Rajinikanth's character, the poor man, was made the main character. When Krissna asked Shanmugasundaram about the \"incomplete pockets\" in the story, Shanmugasundaram replied that it could all be developed over the course of production.<ref name=\"NoAnnamalaiNoBaashha\" /> Shanmugasundaram had been hired at Rajinikanth's suggestion.{{sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=10}}\n\nWhen Krissna met Rajinikanth, he told him that there was a substantial amount of work to be done in the script, but liked the plot.{{sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|pp=10\u201311}}{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=146}} Shortly before the beginning of principal photography, which was scheduled to begin on 11 March and continue its first schedule for ten days,{{sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=11}} only the main cast&nbsp;\u2013 Rajinikanth as the title character, [[Khushbu Sundar|Khushbu]] as his love interest and [[Sarath Babu]] as his friend Ashok&nbsp;\u2013 had been finalised.<ref name=\"NoAnnamalaiNoBaashha\" />{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=149}} Khushbu's character initially had the same name as her, but this was later changed to Subbulakshmi alias \"Subbu\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vikatan.com/oddities/celebrity/16969--2 |title=\u0bb5\u0bbf\u0b95\u0b9f\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bc7\u0b9f\u0bc8: \u0b95\u0bc1\u0bb7\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1 |date=14 March 2012 |website=[[Ananda Vikatan]] |language=ta |trans-title=Vikatan Desk: Khushbu |url-status=live |access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref> Since the script was not complete, there was no proper shooting schedule, and [[Manorama (Tamil actress)|Manorama]] was initially unavailable. But after another film she had signed got cancelled, she was cast in ''Annaamalai'' as the title character's mother Sivagami.<ref name=\"NoAnnamalaiNoBaashha\" /><ref name=\"IE review\" /> [[Radha Ravi]] was cast as Ashok's father Gangadharan.<ref name=\"IE review\" /> He was not interested in playing an elderly character, but agreed to appear in ''Annaamalai'' at Rajinikanth's insistence.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/refrains-old-and-new/article2973933.ece |title=Refrains, old and new |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |date=8 March 2012 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=17 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140417115209/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/refrains-old-and-new/article2973933.ece |archive-date=17 April 2014}}</ref> Pre-production works such as casting and location hunting took place on the day before shooting began.{{sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=14}}{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=146}} Balachander's wife Rajam and their daughter Pushpa Kandhaswamy received the producer credit.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.primevideo.com/detail/0G9H0HF3Q383AVXDYPQ7JURJHX |title=Annamalai |website=[[Prime Video]] |publisher=[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |access-date=16 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\n''Annaamalai'' was launched at AVM Studios at the venue of Pillaiyar temple.{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=15}} [[Principal photography]] began on 11 March 1992.<ref name=\"NoAnnamalaiNoBaashha\" /> After the film's [[muhurat shot]], the first scene to be filmed was a comedy scene where Annaamalai would save Ashok, who has been brought to court for a minor offence. Krissna removed the scene from the final cut as he felt it had no bearing on the script.{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|pp=17\u201318}}\n\nThe scene where Annaamalai enters a ladies' hostel and gets terrified by a snake was shot at Chakra House, Alwarpet.{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|page=19}} A snake was brought specially for the scene. The owner of the snake earlier worked in previous films of Rajinikanth. Suresh asked his assistants Nagappan and [[K. Natraj]] to check the details about the snake charmer. Krissna recalled that he covered his nervousness with his smile. Krissna told cinematographer P. S. Prakash to use zoom lens so that he could adjust a camera according to the situation. After the scene was finished, the members of the crew enjoyed the shot. Krissna congratulated Rajinikanth and asked him how he performed it so well and if it was planned, and Rajinikanth replied it was not planned; expressions in the scene were a result of his fear. In the same scene, Shanmugasundaram came with initial dialogues to convey Annaamalai's fear. Krissna felt that dialogues were redundant in such situation. Rajinikanth insisted to keep ''Kadavule Kadavule'' (Oh God! Oh God!) as the dialogue. Krissna agreed to keep the dialogue as it went well into the situation of the scene.{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|pp=19\u201324}} According to Krissna, nobody on set realised that the snake's mouth was not stitched; it was only after filming ended for that day that the director came to realise that Rajinikanth's life was at risk the entire time.{{sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|pp=25\u201326}}\n\nKrissna wanted the picturisation of \"Vanthenda Paalkaaran\" to be vibrant and colourful stating that he got inspired from the Hindi songs of [[Amitabh Bachchan]]. The scene where Annaamalai shows his face to the camera was extended in slow motion by Krissna as fans would feel as if he was looking towards the audience. The song was choreographed by [[Prabhu Deva]].{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|pp=31\u201334}} The title song \"Annaamalai\" where the title character and Subbu appear in periodic costumes was shot at Fern Hill Palace Hotel while the matching shots were shot at Sivaji Gardens. Krissna shot the song sequence in a technique where the lip sync is perfect while the dance movements being fast revealing that he got inspired from the song \"Mamavukku Koduma\" from ''[[Punnagai Mannan]]'' (1986).{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|pp=35\u201337}} The scene where Annaamalai beats up Sargunam in a one-sided fight was filmed at [[Egmore#Various buildings|Hotel Ambassador Pallava]].{{sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=81}} Filming was completed in 45 working days.{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=146}}\n\n=== Post-production ===\n[[File:Super Star Rajni.gif|thumb|The \"Super Star\" graphic title card]]\n''Annaamalai'' was edited by the duo Ganesh\u2013Kumar.{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=68}} It was the first film to feature the introductory \"Super Star\" graphic title card, where the words 'SUPER' and 'STAR' form in blue dots on the screen followed by R-A-J-N-I in gold, set to the sound of laser beams while the word \"Hey!\" plays in [[Loop (music)|loop]] in the background.<ref name=\"SuperStarTitle\" />{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=148}} This idea was conceived by Krissna, who was inspired by the opening [[gun barrel sequence]] in the [[Production of the James Bond films|James Bond films]], and felt that Rajinikanth, who was becoming a phenomenon, \"warranted a unique logo to go with his name\".{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=89}}\n\nRajinikanth initially objected to the inclusion of the Super Star title card as he felt it was \"brazen self-aggrandisement\" and \"embarrassing\",{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=90}} but Krissna convinced him, saying it would generate large applause.{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|pp=148\u2013149}} Balachander supported Krissna, and asked Rajinikanth, \"What is wrong in Suresh's idea Rajini? People are clapping for your name. It is a great idea and let's go for it\", after which Rajinikanth relented.<ref name=\"SureshKrissnaBehindwoods\" /> The final cut of the film was initially {{convert|14950|feet|metres}}, at a time when the length of Tamil films was restricted to {{convert|14500|feet|metres}}, equal to two hours and forty-five minutes. With the removal of the courtroom scene, the film's final length was reduced by {{convert|450|feet|metres}}.{{sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|pp=17\u201318}}\n\n== Music ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Annaamalai\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Deva (composer)|Deva]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1992\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Lahari Music]]\n| producer   = \n| prev_title = [[Vaigasi Poranthachu]]\n| prev_year  = 1991\n| next_title = [[Suriyan]]\n| next_year  = 1992\n}}\n\nThe soundtrack was composed by [[Deva (composer)|Deva]], with lyrics by [[Vairamuthu]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.raaga.com/channels/tamil/moviedetail.asp?mid=T0001968 |title=Annamalai (1992) |website=[[Raaga.com]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117024856/http://www.raaga.com/channels/tamil/moviedetail.asp?mid=T0001968 |archive-date=17 January 2012 |access-date=8 March 2012}}</ref> It was released under the [[Lahari Music|Lahari]] label.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.jiosaavn.com/album/annamalai/1sm6jY5EXz8_ |title=Annamalai |website=[[JioSaavn]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716035202/https://www.jiosaavn.com/album/annamalai/1sm6jY5EXz8_ |archive-date=16 July 2019 |access-date=16 July 2019}}</ref> ''Annaamalai'' marked Deva's first collaboration with Rajinikanth. Balachander chose him as composer due to a misunderstanding with his usual composer [[Ilaiyaraaja]]. Rajinikanth and Krissna were initially worried with the choice of Deva.{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|pp=29\u201330}} When Krissna met Deva, he had already composed the song \"Annaamalai Annaamalai\" when Vasanth was the director.{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|page=30}} The song is set in the [[Carnatic raga]] known as [[Mohanam]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/music/music-composer-deva-talks-about-tweaking-ragas-and-understanding-film-music-in-his-journey-from-composer-to-singer/article19316698.ece |title=Composer Deva: the monarch of Gaana music |last=Saravanan |first=T. |date=20 July 2017 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=6 June 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181030035929/https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/music/music-composer-deva-talks-about-tweaking-ragas-and-understanding-film-music-in-his-journey-from-composer-to-singer/article19316698.ece |archive-date=30 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n\"Vanthenda Paalkaaran\" was inspired by a Kannada poem which Rajinikanth had suggested; the poem talked about cows as deities, useful to humans in many ways. Vairamuthu grasped the core of the poem and embellished it further, adding an element of contrast between the ever-giving cow and selfish humans who only take from other beings. He also inserted a few ingenious words to boost Rajinikanth's image as a \"mass hero\" of the Tamils, such as \"Ennai Vaazha Vaithadhu Tamizh Paalu\" (It is the milk of love from you Tamils that has given me life).{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|pp=31\u201332}} The song's tune is based on the [[Marathi language|Marathi]] folk song \"Mee Dolkar Daryacha Raja\" (1969).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.filmcompanion.in/the-kannada-and-marathi-roots-of-rajinikanths-first-hero-introduction-song/ |title=The Kannada And Marathi Roots Of Rajinikanth's First Hero Introduction Song |last=Srinivasan |first=Karthik |date=20 November 2018 |website=[[Film Companion]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120104341/https://www.filmcompanion.in/the-kannada-and-marathi-roots-of-rajinikanths-first-hero-introduction-song/# |archive-date=20 November 2018 |access-date=20 November 2018}}</ref> The theme song, which does not appear on the soundtrack and plays during the Super Star graphic title card,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://scroll.in/reel/883765/how-tamil-composer-deva-churned-out-the-hits-a-film-song-should-immediately-register-with-people |title=How Tamil composer Deva rolled out the hits: \u2018A film song should immediately register with people\u2019 |last=Yamunan |first=Sruthisagar |date=24 June 2018 |website=[[Scroll.in]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190906054743/https://scroll.in/reel/883765/how-tamil-composer-deva-churned-out-the-hits-a-film-song-should-immediately-register-with-people |archive-date=6 September 2019 |access-date=6 September 2019}}</ref> was inspired by the [[James Bond Theme]].<ref name=\"NoAnnamalaiNoBaashha\" />\n{{Track listing\n| headline      = \n| extra_column  = Singer(s)\n| total_length  = \n| title1        = Vanthenda Paalkaran\n| extra1        = [[S. P. Balasubrahmanyam]]\n| length1       = 5:06\n| title2        = Annaamalai Annaamalai\n| extra2        = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam, [[K. S. Chithra]]\n| length2       = 4:58\n| title3        = Kondayil Thaazham Poo\n| extra3        = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam, K. S. Chithra\n| length3       = 4:41\n| title4        = Vetri Nichayam\n| extra4        = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam\n| length4       = 4:14\n| title5        = Oru Pen Pura\n| extra5        = [[K. J. Yesudas]]\n| length5       = 5:13\n| title6        = Rekkai Katti Parakudhu\n| extra6        = S. P. Balasubrahmanyam, K. S. Chithra\n| length6       = 4:23\n}}\n\n== Release ==\n''Annaamalai'' was released on 27 June 1992.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.google.co.in/newspapers?nid=P9oYG7HA76QC&dat=19920627&printsec=frontpage&hl=en |title=Annaamalai |date=27 June 1992 |work=[[The Indian Express]] |page=3}}</ref> Its opening was threatened since the new government of [[J. Jayalalithaa]] implemented a new rule where posters of films were prohibited in Madras. Nevertheless, according to Krissna, the lack of promos only increased the hype and worked to the film's advantage;{{sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|p=76}}\n\n== Reception ==\nIn a review dated 3 July, Lalitha Dileep of ''[[The Indian Express]]'' said, \"the film combines good screenplay, proficient direction and first rate acting. The end result is both entertaining and engrossing\". She said the metamorphosis of Annaamalai from a simpleton to a wealthy man was \"done in a plausible manner and with great cinematic finesse\", praised the editing, the cinematography, the music and lyrics, concluding, \"[''Annaamalai''] is enjoyable and touching.\"<ref name=\"IE review\" /> K. Vijiyan of ''[[New Straits Times]]'' wrote on 11 July, \"[''Annaamalai''] will be hit with Rajni's admirers but a disappointment for Balachander's discerning fans who are looking for a story with a difference\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=PqRUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OpADAAAAIBAJ&pg=2717%2C247623 |title=Revenge storyline getting too stale |last=Vijiyan |first=K. |date=11 July 1992 |work=[[New Straits Times]] |page=13}}</ref> A special screening was held for actor [[Sivaji Ganesan]] who told Krissna, \"In my heyday, the camera remained steady while I would move up and down to make an impact as a hero, but you've limited [Rajinikanth's] movements and made the camera whirl around. The dynamism of the shots have helped project heroism better [...] You've showcased another dimension of [Rajinikanth]. The film's plus is its making.\"{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|page=93}}\n\nThe film completed a 175-day run at the box office.{{Sfn|Krissna|Rangarajan|2012|page=69}} It was the highest-grossing film in [[Tamil cinema]] until 1995 when the record was broken by ''[[Baashha]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/regional/will-kabali-be-rajinikanths-most-revered-film-here-are-his-top-10-roles-1434235 |title=Will Kabali be Rajinikanth's Most Revered Film? Here Are His Top 10 Roles |last=Goyal |first=Divya |date=22 July 2016 |website=[[NDTV]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303160854/http://movies.ndtv.com/regional/will-kabali-be-rajinikanths-most-revered-film-here-are-his-top-10-roles-1434235 |archive-date=3 March 2018 |access-date=3 March 2018}}</ref> The collections of ''Annaamalai'' sent tremors everywhere. ''Annaamalai'' exceeded normal regional collections making the film producers all over India sit up and take notice. With ''Annaamalai'', Rajinikanth's range increased and made him the highest-paid actor in India till now. Tamil Manila Congress and DMK ally prioritised 'Annaamalai Cycle', and won the 1996 elections by a huge margin.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/vasans-new-party-to-retain-tmc-as-brand-name/article6647144.ece |title=Vasan's new party to retain TMC as 'brand name' |last=Kolappan |first=B. |date=30 November 2014 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=17 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205163446/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/vasans-new-party-to-retain-tmc-as-brand-name/article6647144.ece |archive-date=5 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/only-rajini-can/articleshow/756523.cms |title=Only Rajini can |last=Govardan |first=D. |date=10 December 2006 |work=[[The Economic Times]] |access-date=15 July 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190715114927/https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/only-rajini-can/articleshow/756523.cms |archive-date=15 July 2019}}</ref> For his performance, Rajinikanth won the Ambika Award for Best Actor.{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=269}} \n\n== Remakes ==\n''Annaamalai'' was remade into [[Telugu language|Telugu]] in 1993 as ''[[Kondapalli Raja]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.telugucinema.com/c/publish/stars/interview_ravirajapinishetty2010_3.php |title=Interview: Ravi Raja Pinisetty |last=Sri |date=15 July 2010 |website=Telugucinema.com |page=3 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101231093534/http://www.telugucinema.com/c/publish/stars/interview_ravirajapinishetty2010_3.php |archive-date=31 December 2010 |access-date=8 March 2012}}</ref> and into [[Kannada]] in 2003 as ''[[Gokarna (film)|Gokarna]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/2004/01/04/stories/2004010408720500.htm |title=2003, a flop for Kannada cinema |last=Venkatasubba Rao |first=K. N. |date=4 January 2004 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=28 February 2018 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228162004/http://www.thehindu.com/2004/01/04/stories/2004010408720500.htm |archive-date=28 February 2018}}</ref> Despite its Telugu remake, the film was also dubbed in that language as ''Birla Ramudu''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.moviefone.com/movie/birla-ramudu/zvRxXAJ6wd3GkO0qJ4smr5/main/ |title=Birla Ramudu (1992) |website=[[Moviefone]] |language=en |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191023041359/https://www.moviefone.com/movie/birla-ramudu/zvRxXAJ6wd3GkO0qJ4smr5/main/ |archive-date=23 October 2019 |access-date=23 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\n<!-- http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/2017/dec/20/debunking-movie-myths-the-annamalai-style-of-blowing-up-cars-1732814.html -->\n''Annaamalai'' set a trend in Tamil cinema: a \"mass introduction song for a hero\".<ref name=\"SureshKrissnaBehindwoods\" /> Additionally, the \"Super Star\" graphic title card continued to feature in many of Rajinikanth's later films like ''[[Veera (1994 film)|Veera]]'' (1994), ''Baashha'' and ''[[Muthu (1995 film)|Muthu]]'' (1995).<ref name=\"SuperStarTitle\" /> [[Jai (actor)|Jai]] stated that his character from ''[[Engaeyum Eppothum]]'' (2011) \"was almost modelled on the lines of Rajini Sir in the first half of [''Annaamalai'']\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/hitman/article5276396.ece |title=Hit-man |last=Rao |first=Subha J |date=27 October 2013 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=17 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140830183553/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/hitman/article5276396.ece |archive-date=30 August 2014}}</ref> Suresh Krishna directed ''[[Arumugam (film)|Aarumugam]]'' in 2009 which critics compared with ''Annaamalai'' due to its similar plot and characterisations.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/true-to-formula/article3021972.ece |title=True to formula |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |date=2 October 2009 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=17 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181030035737/https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/true-to-formula/article3021972.ece# |archive-date=30 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe dialogue \"Naan Solradaiyum Seiven, Soladadeiyum Seiven\" (I'll do what I say, I'll also do what I don't say) attained popularity.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/regional-movies/watch-all-the-rajini-fans-thalaiva-s-five-iconic-dialogues/story-0dFbrhMGiFejgRQxs9oZeL.html |title=WATCH: All the Rajini fans... Thalaiva\u2019s five iconic dialogues |last=Mishra |first=Nivedita |date=12 December 2014 |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |access-date=28 February 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228223156/https://www.hindustantimes.com/regional-movies/watch-all-the-rajini-fans-thalaiva-s-five-iconic-dialogues/story-0dFbrhMGiFejgRQxs9oZeL.html |archive-date=28 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe scenes from the film were parodied in ''[[Paarthale Paravasam]]'' (2001),<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Paarthale Paravasam |type=motion picture |language=ta |publisher=[[Kavithalayaa Productions]] |year=2001 |time=6:30 to 7:14 |time-caption=From}}</ref> ''[[Boss Engira Bhaskaran]]'' (2010),<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movie-reviews/Boss-Engira-Bhaskaran/movie-review/6547029.cms |title=Boss Engira Bhaskaran Movie Review |last=Ravi |first=Bhama Devi |date=10 September 2010 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=17 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150731015349/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movie-reviews/Boss-Engira-Bhaskaran/movie-review/6547029.cms |archive-date=31 July 2015}}</ref> and ''[[Thamizh Padam]]'' (2010).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/tamil-padam-review-tamil-pclx0Wibgbecd.html |title=Tamil Padam |date=29 January 2010 |website=[[Sify]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228162913/http://www.sify.com/movies/tamil-padam-review-tamil-pclx0Wibgbecd.html |archive-date=28 February 2018 |access-date=28 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"SureshKrissnaBehindwoods\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-cinema-news-16/director-suresh-krissna-on-25-years-of-rajinis-film-annamalai.html |title=Rajini was stopped at the entrance of Poes Garden |last=Bhavanishankar |first=Jyothsna |date=27 June 2017 |website=Behindwoods |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6xYzdCvFo?url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-cinema-news-16/director-suresh-krissna-on-25-years-of-rajinis-film-annamalai.html |archive-date=28 February 2018 |access-date=28 February 2018}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"SuperStarTitle\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.filmcompanion.in/a-superstar-career-through-titles-rajinikanth-aboorva-raagangal-to-2-0/ |title=A Superstar Career Through Titles |last=Shivakumar |first=Vivek |date=11 December 2018 |website=[[Film Companion]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714155517/https://www.filmcompanion.in/a-superstar-career-through-titles-rajinikanth-aboorva-raagangal-to-2-0/ |archive-date=14 July 2019 |access-date=15 July 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"NoAnnamalaiNoBaashha\">{{Cite news |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/without-annamalai-there-wouldnt-be-baashha/articleshow/59322761.cms |title=Without Annamalai, there wouldn't be Baashha |last=Krissna |first=Suresh |date=27 June 2017 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=28 February 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228223001/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/without-annamalai-there-wouldnt-be-baashha/articleshow/59322761.cms |archive-date=28 February 2018 |last2=Suganth |first2=M. |author-link=Suresh Krissna}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"IE review\">{{Cite news |url=https://news.google.co.in/newspapers?nid=P9oYG7HA76QC&dat=19920703&printsec=frontpage&hl=en |title=Soul-mates forever |last=Dileep |first=Lalitha |date=3 July 1992 |work=[[The Indian Express]] |page=7}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{Cite book |title=My Days with Baasha |last=Krissna |first=Suresh |last2=Rangarajan |first2=Malathi |publisher=Westland Ltd. |year=2012 |isbn=978-93-8162-629-0 |ref=harv |author-link=Suresh Krissna}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Rajinikanth: The Definitive Biography |title-link=Rajinikanth: The Definitive Biography |last=Ramachandran |first=Naman |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |year=2014 |isbn=978-81-8475-796-5 |ref=harv |author-link=Naman Ramachandran |orig-year=2012}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote|Annamalai}}\n* {{IMDb title|0139859}}\n\n{{Kavithalaya Productions}}\n{{Suresh Krissna}}\n\n[[Category:1990s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:1990s action drama films]]\n[[Category:1990s buddy films]]\n[[Category:1992 films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Suresh Krissna]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Deva (composer)]]\n[[Category:Indian action drama films]]\n[[Category:Indian buddy films]]\n[[Category:Indian films about revenge]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Tamil remakes of Hindi films]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Annaamalai"}
{"title_page": "Pan-African Congress", "text_new": "{{for|South African political party|Pan Africanist Congress of Azania}}\nThe '''Pan-African Congress''' \u2014 following on from the [[first Pan-African Conference]] of 1900 in [[London]] \u2014 was a series of eight meetings, held in 1919 in [[Paris]] (1st Pan-African Congress), 1921 in London (2nd Pan-African Congress), 1923 in London (3rd Pan-African Congress), 1927 in [[New York City]] (4th Pan-African Congress), 1945 in [[Manchester]] (5th Pan-African Congress), 1974 in [[Dar es Salaam]] (6th Pan-African Congress),<ref>Hill, Sylvia (2007), [http://www.noeasyvictories.org/select/08_hill.php \"From the Sixth Pan-African Congress to the Free South Africa Movement\"], in William Minter, Gail Hovey, and Charles Cobb Jr. (eds), ''No Easy Victories: African Liberation and American Activists over a Half Century, 1950\u20132000'', Trenton, New Jersey: Africa World Press.</ref> 1994 in [[Kampala]] (7th Pan-African Congress),<ref>Guest Editor's Introduction (June 1996), [http://houseofknowledge.org.uk/site/documents/neoGarveyismCorner/Report%20on%207th%20PAC--from%20the%20USA.pdf \"Rebuilding The Pan African Movement, A Report on the 7th Pan African Congress\"], ''African Journal of Political Science''. New Series Vol. 1, No. I.</ref><ref>Essack, Karrim (11 May 1994), [http://global-panafricanmovement.net/front-page/the-7th-pan-african-congress-in-perspective-by-karrim-essack.html \"The 7th Pan-African Congress in Perspective\"]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Global Pan African Movement, 10 October 2012.</ref> and 2014 in [[Johannesburg]] (8th Pan-African Congress)<ref>Horne, David L. (30 January 2014), [http://ourweekly.com/news/2014/jan/30/pan-african-step-forward/ \"A Pan African Step Forward\"], ''Our Weekly'' (Los Angeles).</ref><ref>Bunsee, Benny (24 January 2014), [http://mg.co.za/article/2014-01-23-arabs-and-the-west-must-pay-for-slavery-says-pan-african-congress \"Arabs and the West must pay for slavery, says Pan-African Congress\"], ''[[Mail & Guardian]]''.</ref> that were intended to address the issues facing [[Africa]] as a result of [[Europe]]an colonization of most of the continent.\n\nThe Pan-African Congress gained the reputation as a peace maker for [[decolonization of Africa|decolonization in Africa]] and in the [[West Indies]]. It made significant advance for the [[Pan-Africanism|Pan-African]] cause. One of the demands was to end colonial rule and end racial discrimination, against imperialism and it demanded human rights and equality of economic opportunity. The manifesto given by the Pan-African Congress included the political and economic demands of the Congress for a new world context of international cooperation.\n\n== Background ==\n[[Colonialism|Colonial]] powers in Africa wanted native Africans to wait patiently for limited [[concession (politics)|political concessions]] and better career opportunities. Due to their exclusion from the negotiations of the 1919 [[Treaty of Versailles]] \u2014 the most important of the peace treaties that brought [[World War I]] to an end \u2014 black ex-servicemen and educated urban classes became disillusioned. Because colonialism had been built on the foundation of capitalism, [[Socialism|socialist]] ideas of equality and global collaboration appealed to these budding revolutionaries.\n\nA letter from [[Jamaica]]n writer and socialist [[Claude McKay]] to [[Leon Trotsky]] in 1922 refers to the experience of black soldiers:\n\n{{cquote|They had been disillusioned with the European war, they kept on having frightful clashes with English and American soldiers, besides the fact the authorities treated them completely differently from the white soldiers... I was working at that time in London in a [[Workers' Socialist Federation|communist group]]. Our group provided the club of Negro soldiers with revolutionary newspapers and literature which had nothing.}}\n\n==1st Pan-African Congress==\n\n[[File:Pan-African Congress, Paris, February 19-22, 1919.png|thumb|Pan-African Congress, [[Paris]], France, February 19\u201322, 1919]]\nIn February 1919, the first Pan-African Congress was organized by [[W. E. B. Du Bois]] and [[Ida Gibbs Hunt]], wife of US Consul [[William Henry Hunt (diplomat)|William Henry Hunt]], who was at that time working at the American consulate in [[Saint-\u00c9tienne]], France.<ref>{{cite book|last=Roberts|first=Brian|title=Artistic Ambassadors: Literary and International Representation of the New Negro Era|year=2013|publisher=University of Virginia Press|location=Charlottesville|pages=121\u201322}}</ref> There were 57 delegates representing 15 countries, a smaller number than originally intended because British and American governments refused to issue passports to their citizens who had planned on attending.<ref>{{cite book|last=Painter|first=Nell Irvin|authorlink=Nell Irvin Painter|title=Standing at Armageddon: A Grassroots History of the Progressive Era|year=2008|publisher=W.W. Norton & Company|location=New York|isbn=978-0-393-33192-9|page=355}}</ref> Their main task was petitioning the [[Versailles Peace Conference]] held in Paris at that time. Among their demands were that:\n* [[Allies of World War I|The Allies]] should be in charge of the administration of former territories in Africa as a [[Condominium (international law)|Condominium]] on behalf of the Africans who were living there.\n* Africa be granted home rule and Africans should take part in governing their countries as fast as their development permits until at some specified time in the future.\n\n===Delegates===\nAmong the delegates were:<ref>Worley, H. F., and C. G. Contee (April 1970), \"The Worley Report on the Pan-African Congress of 1919\", reproduced in ''[[Journal of Negro History]]'', Vol. 55, No. 2, pp. 140\u201343.</ref>\n* [[Eliezer Cadet]], [[Universal Negro Improvement Association]]\n* [[Gratien Candace]], [[Guadeloupe]]\n* [[Blaise Diagne]], [[Senegal]], and French Commissioner General of the [[Minister of Overseas France|Ministry of Colonies]]\n* [[William Jernagin]], [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]], United States\n* [[Charles D. B. King]], Liberia\n* [[Richard R. Wright]]\n* [[Robert Russa Moton]]\n\n== 2nd Pan-African Congress ==\n[[File:Deuxi\u00e8me Congr\u00e8s Panafricain, au Palais Mondial, \u00e0 Bruxelles en septembre 1921 01.jpg|thumb|right|Session in the Palais Mondial, Brussels, 1921]]\nIn 1921, the Second Pan-African Congress met in several sessions in [[London]], [[Brussels]] and Paris, during August (28, 29, and 31) and September (2, 3, 5 and 6).<ref>[https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/workers/civil-rights/crisis/1100-crisis-v23n01-w133.pdf ''The Crisis''], Vol. 23, No. 1 (November 1921).</ref> As [[W. E. B. Du Bois]] reported in ''[[The Crisis]]'' in November that year, represented at this congress were \"26 different groups of people of Negro descent: namely, British Nigeria, Gold Coast and Sierra Leone; the Egyptian Sudan, British East Africa, former German East Africa; French Senegal, the French Congo and Madagascar; Belgian Congo; Portuguese St. Thom\u00e9, Angola and Mozambique; Liberia; Abyssinia; Haiti; British Jamaica and Grenada; French Martinique and Guadeloupe; British Guiana; the United States of America, Negroes resident in England, France, Belgium and Portugal, and fraternal visitors from India, Morocco, the Philippines and Annam.\"<ref>[https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/workers/civil-rights/crisis/1100-crisis-v23n01-w133.pdf \"Manifesto to The League of Nations\"], ''The Crisis'', Vol. 23, No. 1 (November 1921), p. 18.</ref> There was an Indian revolutionary who took part, [[Shapurji Saklatvala]], and a journalist from the Gold Coast named W. F. Hutchinson who spoke. This session of the Congress was the most focused for change of all the meetings thus far. At the London session, resolutions were adopted, later restated by Du Bois in his \"Manifesto To the League of Nations\":<ref>Lewis, David, ''W. E. B. Du Bois: A Biography'', 2009, pp. 414\u201315.</ref><ref>Du Bois, W. E. B. , [https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/workers/civil-rights/crisis/1100-crisis-v23n01-w133.pdf \"To the World (Manifesto to The League of Nations.)\"], Opinion, ''The Crisis'', Vol. 23, No. 1 (November 1921), p. 7.</ref>\n\n{{cquote|England, with all her Pax Britannic, her courts of justice, established commerce, and a certain apparent recognition of Native laws and customs, has nevertheless systematically fostered ignorance among the Natives, has enslaved them, and is still enslaving them, has usually declined even to try to train black and brown men in real self-government, to recognise civilised black folk as civilised, or to grant to coloured colonies those rights of self government which it freely gives to white men.}}\n\nThe only dissenting voices were these of [[Blaise Diagne]] and [[Gratien Candace]], French politicians of African and Guadeloupian descent, who represented [[Senegal]] and Guadeloupe in the [[French Chamber of Deputies]]. They soon abandoned the idea of Pan-Africanism because they advocated equal rights inside the French citizenship and thought the London Manifesto declaration too dangerously extreme.\n\nThe Brussels sessions were hosted at the [[Palais Mondial]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kirschke|first1=Amy|editor1-last=Benesch|editor1-first=Klaus|editor2=Genevi\u00e8ve Fabre|title=African Diasporas in the New and Old Worlds: Consciousness and Imagination edited by|date=2004|publisher=Rodopi|page=246|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=AazP5n2oJYUC&lpg=PA246&dq=%22Palais%20Mondial%22%20%22pan-african%20conference%22&pg=PA246#v=onepage&q=%22Palais%20Mondial%22%20%22pan-african%20conference%22&f=false|chapter=Du Bois, The Crisis and Images of Africa and the Diaspora}}</ref>\n\n== 3rd Pan-African Congress ==\nIn 1923, the Third Pan-African Congress was held in London and in [[Lisbon]]. This meeting was totally unorganized. This meeting also repeated the demands such as self-rule, the problems in the [[African diaspora|Diaspora]] and the African-European relationship. The following was addressed at the meeting:\n\n* The development of Africa should be for the benefit of Africans and not merely for the profits of Europeans.\n* There should be home rule and a responsible government for British West Africa and the [[British West Indies]].\n* The Abolition of the pretension of a white minority to dominate a black majority in Kenya, [[Rhodesia]] and South Africa.\n* [[Lynching]] and mob law in the US should be suppressed.\n\nBefore the Congress met in London, [[Isaac B\u00e9ton]] of the French Committee wrote a letter to Du Bois, telling him that the French group would not be sending delegates. However, in one of the reports he published in the ''[[Crisis]]'', Du Bois drew on words spoken by [[Ida Gibbs Hunt]] and [[Rayford Logan]] to imply that the French Committee had sent delegates. As long-time African-American residents of France, Hunt and Logan had travelled independently to the meeting, and Hunt and B\u00e9ton were perturbed that Du Bois had implied they represented France.<ref>{{cite book|last=Roberts|first=Brian Russell|title=Artistic Ambassadors: Literary and International Representation of the New Negro Era|year=2013|publisher=University of Virginia Press|location=Charlottesville|pages=125\u2013126}}</ref>\n\n== 4th Pan-African Congress ==\nIn 1927, The Fourth Pan-African Congress was held in [[New York City]] and adopted resolutions that were similar to the Third Pan-African Congress meetings.<ref>{{cite web | title=The Pan-African Vision | work=The Story of Africa: Between World Wars (1914\u20131945) | publisher=BBC News | accessdate=16 April 2008| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/africa/features/storyofafrica/13chapter5.shtml }}</ref>\n\n== 5th Pan-African Congress ==\n\n[[File:Manchester-fifth-pan-african-conference-1.jpg|thumb|The commemorating plaque in [[Manchester]]]]\n\nThe Fifth Pan-African Congress was held in [[Manchester]], United Kingdom, from 15th\u201321st October 1945. It followed the foundation of the [[Pan-African Federation]] in Manchester in 1944.<ref>[[Hakim Adi|Adi, Hakim]] (2009), \"George Padmore and the 1945 Manchester Pan-African Congress\", in Baptiste, Fitzroy, and Rupert Lewis (eds), ''[http://George%20Padmore:%20Pan-African%20Revolutionary George Padmore: Pan-African Revolutionary]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}''. Kingston, Jamaica: [[Ian Randle Publishers]].</ref> The Congress took place at the [[Chorlton-on-Medlock|Chorlton-upon-Medlock]] Town Hall, which was decorated with the flags of the [[Republic of Haiti (1859\u20131957)|Republic of Haiti]], [[Ethiopia]], and [[Liberia]], the only three independent black nations in 1945.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wcml.org.uk/our-collections/object-of-the-month/1945-panafrican-congress-in-manchester/|title=1945 Pan-African Congress in Manchester|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The Fifth Congress is viewed as the most significant, being held just months after the end of the [[World War II|Second World War]]. The war had been fought in the name of freedom, however around the globe, millions of Africans and [[African diaspora|Afro-Diaspora]] populations lived under European [[Colonialism|colonial rule]]. Historian Christian H\u00f8gsbjerg writes in his essay ''Remembering the Fifth Pan African Congress'' that the aftermath of WWII gave rise to a \u201cnew mood of militancy among colonial Africans, Asians and West Indians.\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lucas.leeds.ac.uk/article/remembering-the-fifth-pan-african-congress-christian-hogsbjerg/|title=Remembering the Fifth Pan-African Congress|last=Christian|first=H\u00f8gsbjerg|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nThe Fifth Congress was also unique in comparison to the four earlier Congresses as it was attended by delegates from across the African Diaspora, such as [[Afro-Caribbean people|Afro-Caribbean\u2019s]], [[African Americans|African American\u2019s]], and [[Black British people|Black Briton\u2019s]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/manchester/content/articles/2005/10/14/151005_pan_african_congress_feature.shtml|title=Manchester And The Pan-African Movement|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The Congress made demands for Independence as well as condemning [[imperialism]], [[racial discrimination]], and [[capitalism]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shadowandact.com/details-on-the-fifth-pan-african-congress-and-pan-african-film-installation-london|title=Details on the Fifth Pan-African Congress and Pan-African Film Installation (London)|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n=== Delegates ===\nOrganised by the influential [[Trinidadians and Tobagonians|Trinidadian]] pan-Africanist [[George Padmore]] and Ghanaian independence leader [[Kwame Nkrumah]], the Fifth Pan-African Congress was attended by over 90 delegates, including 26 from Africa, 33 from the West Indies and 35 from various British organisations,including the [[West African Students Union]].There were also a few South Asian delegates in attendance.Also, in attendance were several \u00a0black activists living in Manchester.  Delegates included scholars, intellectuals and political activists who would later go on to become influential leaders in various [[African independence movements]] and [[Civil rights movement|American civil rights movements]]. The presence of 77-year-old [[W. E. B. Du Bois]] was historic, as he had organized the First Pan-African Congress in 1919.\n\nAmong the delegates were:\n\n* [[Jomo Kenyatta]], Kenya\n* [[W. E. B. Du Bois]], United States\n\n*[[Hastings Banda]], Malawi\n*[[Kwame Nkrumah]], Ghana\n*[[Dudley Thompson]], Jamaica\n*[[Obafemi Awolowo]] and [[Jaja Wachuku]], Nigeria\n*[[Len Johnson (boxer)|Len Johnson]], Britain\n*[[Peter Abrahams]], South Africa \u00a0\n*[[Amy Ashwood Garvey]], Jamaica\n\nIt also led partially to the creation of the [[Pan-African Federation]], founded in 1946 by Nkrumah and Kenyatta.\n\nThe British Press scarcely mentioned the conference. A number of resolutions were passed, among them the criminalization of [[racial discrimination]] and the main resolution decrying [[imperialism]] and [[capitalism]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Katzenellenbogen|first1=Simon|title=The 1945 Pan-African Congress and its Aftermath at The Manchester Civic Celebration, October 13th to 15th, 1995|url=http://www.hartford-hwp.com/archives/30/058.html|accessdate=1 March 2017|date=2 May 1995}}</ref>\n\n[[Ahmed Iqbal Ullah Race Relations Resource Centre|The Ahmed Iqbal Ullah Race Relations Resource Centre]] holds a collection of material that relates to the 5th Pan-African Congress. It spans from 1945-2005 and includes leaflets, invites, photographs, press releases, letters, a programme of events and memories from attendees captured as audio recordings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://documents.manchester.ac.uk/display.aspx?DocID=35308%20|title=Pan-African Congress 1945 and 1995 archive|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==The significance of the Pan-African movement and the Fifth Congress==\n\nPan-Africanism is aimed at the economic, intellectual and political cooperation of the African countries. It demands that the riches of the continent be used for the enlistment of its people. It calls for the financial and economic unification of markets and a new political landscape for the continent. Even though Pan-Africanism as a movement began in 1776, it was the fifth Pan-African congress that advanced Pan-Africanism and applied it to decolonize the African continent.<ref>{{cite web | title=Road to Pan-Africanism|first=Motsoko |last=Pheko| work=The Sowetan| date=15 November 1999 | url=http://www.panafricanperspective.com/pheko.htm}}</ref>\n\nThe people in Manchester were politically conscious and that was one of the reasons why it was selected as the venue for the fifth Pan-African congress. The fifth congress was organized by people of African origin living in Manchester. According to the Mancunian historian Simon Katzenellenboggen it has a great significance as it was an important step towards the end of those imperial powers in Africa. Unlike the four earlier congresses, the fifth one involved people from the African Diaspora, including Afro-Caribbeans and Afro-Americans. Manchester had a significant part to play in helping the African countries to march forward in their fight to independence.<ref>{{cite web |title=It began in Manchester \u2014 Manchester and The Pan-African Movement |publisher=BBC News; Black History Month |date=14 October 2005| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/manchester/content/articles/2005/10/14/151005_pan_african_congress_feature.shtml}}\n</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[First Pan-African Conference]]\n* [[Pan-Africanism]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Pan-African Congress}}\n* [https://snccdigital.org/our-voices/internationalism/part-4/ SNCC Digital Gateway: Organizing 6PAC] Digital documentary website created by the SNCC Legacy Project and Duke University, telling the story of the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee & grassroots organizing from the inside-out\n* [http://lucas.leeds.ac.uk/article/remembering-the-fifth-pan-african-congress-christian-hogsbjerg/ \"Remembering the Fifth Pan-African Congress - Christian H\u00f8gsbjerg], ''[[Leeds African Studies Bulletin]]'', 77 (2015\u201316). \n* B. F. Bankie, [http://www.ghanansem.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=107&Itemid=146 \"The 'Key Link' \u2013 some London notes towards the 7th Pan-African Congress\"], ''Ghana Nsem'', 2001.\n\n{{W. E. B. Du Bois|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:International conferences]]\n[[Category:Anti-racist organizations in Africa]]\n[[Category:Pan-African organizations]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|South African political party|Pan Africanist Congress of Azania}}\nThe '''Pan-African Congress''' \u2014 following on from the [[first Pan-African Conference]] of 1900 in [[London]] \u2014 was a series of eight meetings, held in 1919 in [[Paris]] (1st Pan-African Congress), 1921 in London (2nd Pan-African Congress), 1923 in London (3rd Pan-African Congress), 1927 in [[New York City]] (4th Pan-African Congress), 1945 in [[Manchester]] (5th Pan-African Congress), 1974 in [[Dar es Salaam]] (6th Pan-African Congress),<ref>Hill, Sylvia (2007), [http://www.noeasyvictories.org/select/08_hill.php \"From the Sixth Pan-African Congress to the Free South Africa Movement\"], in William Minter, Gail Hovey, and Charles Cobb Jr. (eds), ''No Easy Victories: African Liberation and American Activists over a Half Century, 1950\u20132000'', Trenton, New Jersey: Africa World Press.</ref> 1994 in [[Kampala]] (7th Pan-African Congress),<ref>Guest Editor's Introduction (June 1996), [http://houseofknowledge.org.uk/site/documents/neoGarveyismCorner/Report%20on%207th%20PAC--from%20the%20USA.pdf \"Rebuilding The Pan African Movement, A Report on the 7th Pan African Congress\"], ''African Journal of Political Science''. New Series Vol. 1, No. I.</ref><ref>Essack, Karrim (11 May 1994), [http://global-panafricanmovement.net/front-page/the-7th-pan-african-congress-in-perspective-by-karrim-essack.html \"The 7th Pan-African Congress in Perspective\"]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Global Pan African Movement, 10 October 2012.</ref> and 2014 in [[Johannesburg]] (8th Pan-African Congress)<ref>Horne, David L. (30 January 2014), [http://ourweekly.com/news/2014/jan/30/pan-african-step-forward/ \"A Pan African Step Forward\"], ''Our Weekly'' (Los Angeles).</ref><ref>Bunsee, Benny (24 January 2014), [http://mg.co.za/article/2014-01-23-arabs-and-the-west-must-pay-for-slavery-says-pan-african-congress \"Arabs and the West must pay for slavery, says Pan-African Congress\"], ''[[Mail & Guardian]]''.</ref> that were intended to address the issues facing [[Africa]] as a result of [[Europe]]an colonization of most of the continent.\n\nThe Pan-African Congress gained the reputation as a peace maker for [[decolonization of Africa|decolonization in Africa]] and in the [[West Indies]]. It made significant advance for the [[Pan-Africanism|Pan-African]] cause. One of the demands was to end colonial rule and end racial discrimination, against imperialism and it demanded human rights and equality of economic opportunity. The manifesto given by the Pan-African Congress included the political and economic demands of the Congress for a new world context of international cooperation.\n\n== Background ==\n[[Colonialism|Colonial]] powers in Africa wanted native Africans to wait patiently for limited [[concession (politics)|political concessions]] and better career opportunities. Due to their exclusion from the negotiations of the 1919 [[Treaty of Versailles]] \u2014 the most important of the peace treaties that brought [[World War I]] to an end \u2014 black ex-servicemen and educated urban classes became disillusioned. Because colonialism had been built on the foundation of capitalism, [[Socialism|socialist]] ideas of equality and global collaboration appealed to these budding revolutionaries.\n\nA letter from [[Jamaica]]n writer and socialist [[Claude McKay]] to [[Leon Trotsky]] in 1922 refers to the experience of black soldiers:\n\n{{cquote|They had been disillusioned with the European war, they kept on having frightful clashes with English and American soldiers, besides the fact the authorities treated them completely differently from the white soldiers... I was working at that time in London in a [[Workers' Socialist Federation|communist group]]. Our group provided the club of Negro soldiers with revolutionary newspapers and literature which had nothing.}}\n\n==1st Pan-African Congress==\n\n[[File:Pan-African Congress, Paris, February 19-22, 1919.png|thumb|Pan-African Congress, [[Paris]], France, February 19\u201322, 1919]]\nIn February 1919, the first Pan-African Congress was organized by [[W. E. B. Du Bois]] and [[Ida Gibbs Hunt]], wife of US Consul [[William Henry Hunt (diplomat)|William Henry Hunt]], who was at that time working at the American consulate in [[Saint-\u00c9tienne]], France.<ref>{{cite book|last=Roberts|first=Brian|title=Artistic Ambassadors: Literary and International Representation of the New Negro Era|year=2013|publisher=University of Virginia Press|location=Charlottesville|pages=121\u201322}}</ref> There were 57 delegates representing 15 countries, a smaller number than originally intended because British and American governments refused to issue passports to their citizens who had planned on attending.<ref>{{cite book|last=Painter|first=Nell Irvin|authorlink=Nell Irvin Painter|title=Standing at Armageddon: A Grassroots History of the Progressive Era|year=2008|publisher=W.W. Norton & Company|location=New York|isbn=978-0-393-33192-9|page=355}}</ref> Their main task was petitioning the [[Versailles Peace Conference]] held in Paris at that time. Among their demands were that:\n* [[Allies of World War I|The Allies]] should be in charge of the administration of former territories in Africa as a [[Condominium (international law)|Condominium]] on behalf of the Africans who were living there.\n* Africa be granted home rule and Africans should take part in governing their countries as fast as their development permits until at some specified time in the future.\n\n===Delegates===\nAmong the delegates were:<ref>Worley, H. F., and C. G. Contee (April 1970), \"The Worley Report on the Pan-African Congress of 1919\", reproduced in ''[[Journal of Negro History]]'', Vol. 55, No. 2, pp. 140\u201343.</ref>\n* [[Eliezer Cadet]], [[Universal Negro Improvement Association]]\n* [[Gratien Candace]], [[Guadeloupe]]\n* [[Blaise Diagne]], [[Senegal]], and French Commissioner General of the [[Minister of Overseas France|Ministry of Colonies]]\n* [[William Jernagin]], [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]], United States\n* [[Charles D. B. King]], Liberia\n* [[Richard R. Wright]]\n* [[Robert Russa Moton]]\n\n== 2nd Pan-African Congress ==\n[[File:Deuxi\u00e8me Congr\u00e8s Panafricain, au Palais Mondial, \u00e0 Bruxelles en septembre 1921 01.jpg|thumb|right|Session in the Palais Mondial, Brussels, 1921]]\nIn 1921, the Second Pan-African Congress met in several sessions in [[London]], [[Brussels]] and Paris, during August (28, 29, and 31) and September (2, 3, 5 and 6).<ref>[https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/workers/civil-rights/crisis/1100-crisis-v23n01-w133.pdf ''The Crisis''], Vol. 23, No. 1 (November 1921).</ref> As [[W. E. B. Du Bois]] reported in ''[[The Crisis]]'' in November that year, represented at this congress were \"26 different groups of people of Negro descent: namely, British Nigeria, Gold Coast and Sierra Leone; the Egyptian Sudan, British East Africa, former German East Africa; French Senegal, the French Congo and Madagascar; Belgian Congo; Portuguese St. Thom\u00e9, Angola and Mozambique; Liberia; Abyssinia; Haiti; British Jamaica and Grenada; French Martinique and Guadeloupe; British Guiana; the United States of America, Negroes resident in England, France, Belgium and Portugal, and fraternal visitors from India, Morocco, the Philippines and Annam.\"<ref>[https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/workers/civil-rights/crisis/1100-crisis-v23n01-w133.pdf \"Manifesto to The League of Nations\"], ''The Crisis'', Vol. 23, No. 1 (November 1921), p. 18.</ref> There was an Indian revolutionary who took part, [[Shapurji Saklatvala]], and a journalist from the Gold Coast named W. F. Hutchinson who spoke. This session of the Congress was the most focused for change of all the meetings thus far. At the London session, resolutions were adopted, later restated by Du Bois in his \"Manifesto To the League of Nations\":<ref>Lewis, David, ''W. E. B. Du Bois: A Biography'', 2009, pp. 414\u201315.</ref><ref>Du Bois, W. E. B. , [https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/workers/civil-rights/crisis/1100-crisis-v23n01-w133.pdf \"To the World (Manifesto to The League of Nations.)\"], Opinion, ''The Crisis'', Vol. 23, No. 1 (November 1921), p. 7.</ref>\n\n{{cquote|England, with all her Pax Britannic, her courts of justice, established commerce, and a certain apparent recognition of Native laws and customs, has nevertheless systematically fostered ignorance among the Natives, has enslaved them, and is still enslaving them, has usually declined even to try to train black and brown men in real self-government, to recognise civilised black folk as civilised, or to grant to coloured colonies those rights of self government which it freely gives to white men.}}\n\nThe only dissenting voices were these of [[Blaise Diagne]] and [[Gratien Candace]], French politicians of African and Guadeloupian descent, who represented [[Senegal]] and Guadeloupe in the [[French Chamber of Deputies]]. They soon abandoned the idea of Pan-Africanism because they advocated equal rights inside the French citizenship and thought the London Manifesto declaration too dangerously extreme.\n\nThe Brussels sessions were hosted at the [[Palais Mondial]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kirschke|first1=Amy|editor1-last=Benesch|editor1-first=Klaus|editor2=Genevi\u00e8ve Fabre|title=African Diasporas in the New and Old Worlds: Consciousness and Imagination edited by|date=2004|publisher=Rodopi|page=246|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=AazP5n2oJYUC&lpg=PA246&dq=%22Palais%20Mondial%22%20%22pan-african%20conference%22&pg=PA246#v=onepage&q=%22Palais%20Mondial%22%20%22pan-african%20conference%22&f=false|chapter=Du Bois, The Crisis and Images of Africa and the Diaspora}}</ref>\n\n== 3rd Pan-African Congress ==\nIn 1923, the Third Pan-African Congress was held in London and in [[Lisbon]]. This meeting was totally unorganized. This meeting also repeated the demands such as self-rule, the problems in the [[African diaspora|Diaspora]] and the African-European relationship. The following was addressed at the meeting:\n\n* The development of Africa should be for the benefit of Africans and not merely for the profits of Europeans.\n* There should be home rule and a responsible government for British West Africa and the [[British West Indies]].\n* The Abolition of the pretension of a white minority to dominate a black majority in Kenya, [[Rhodesia]] and South Africa.\n* [[Lynching]] and mob law in the US should be suppressed.\n\nBefore the Congress met in London, [[Isaac B\u00e9ton]] of the French Committee wrote a letter to Du Bois, telling him that the French group would not be sending delegates. However, in one of the reports he published in the ''[[Crisis]]'', Du Bois drew on words spoken by [[Ida Gibbs Hunt]] and [[Rayford Logan]] to imply that the French Committee had sent delegates. As long-time African-American residents of France, Hunt and Logan had travelled independently to the meeting, and Hunt and B\u00e9ton were perturbed that Du Bois had implied they represented France.<ref>{{cite book|last=Roberts|first=Brian Russell|title=Artistic Ambassadors: Literary and International Representation of the New Negro Era|year=2013|publisher=University of Virginia Press|location=Charlottesville|pages=125\u2013126}}</ref>\n\n== 4th Pan-African Congress ==\nIn 1927, The Fourth Pan-African Congress was held in [[New York City]] and adopted resolutions that were similar to the Third Pan-African Congress meetings.<ref>{{cite web | title=The Pan-African Vision | work=The Story of Africa: Between World Wars (1914\u20131945) | publisher=BBC News | accessdate=16 April 2008| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/africa/features/storyofafrica/13chapter5.shtml }}</ref>\n\n== 5th Pan-African Congress ==\n\n[[File:Manchester-fifth-pan-african-conference-1.jpg|thumb|The commemorating plaque in [[Manchester]]]]\n\nThe Fifth Pan-African Congress was held in [[Manchester]], United Kingdom, from 15th\u201321st October 1945. It followed the foundation of the [[Pan-African Federation]] in Manchester in 1944.<ref>[[Hakim Adi|Adi, Hakim]] (2009), \"George Padmore and the 1945 Manchester Pan-African Congress\", in Baptiste, Fitzroy, and Rupert Lewis (eds), ''[http://George%20Padmore:%20Pan-African%20Revolutionary George Padmore: Pan-African Revolutionary]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}''. Kingston, Jamaica: [[Ian Randle Publishers]].</ref> The Congress took place at the [[Chorlton-on-Medlock|Chorlton-upon-Medlock]] Town Hall, which was decorated with the flags of the [[Republic of Haiti (1859\u20131957)|Republic of Haiti]], [[Ethiopia]], and [[Liberia]], the only three independent black nations in 1945.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wcml.org.uk/our-collections/object-of-the-month/1945-panafrican-congress-in-manchester/|title=1945 Pan-African Congress in Manchester|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The Fifth Congress is viewed as the most significant, being held just months after the end of the [[World War II|Second World War]]. The war had been fought in the name of freedom, however around the globe, millions of Africans and [[African diaspora|Afro-Diaspora]] populations lived under European [[Colonialism|colonial rule]]. The Fifth Congress was also unique in comparison to the four earlier Congresses as it was attended by delegates from across the African Diaspora, such as [[Afro-Caribbean people|Afro-Caribbean\u2019s]], [[African Americans|African American\u2019s]], and [[Black British people|Black Briton\u2019s]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/manchester/content/articles/2005/10/14/151005_pan_african_congress_feature.shtml|title=Manchester And The Pan-African Movement|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The Congress made demands for Independence as well as condemning [[imperialism]], [[racial discrimination]], and [[capitalism]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shadowandact.com/details-on-the-fifth-pan-african-congress-and-pan-african-film-installation-london|title=Details on the Fifth Pan-African Congress and Pan-African Film Installation (London)|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n=== Delegates ===\nOrganised by the influential [[Trinidadians and Tobagonians|Trinidadian]] pan-Africanist [[George Padmore]] and Ghanaian independence leader [[Kwame Nkrumah]], the Fifth Pan-African Congress was attended by over 90 delegates, including 26 from Africa, 33 from the West Indies and 35 from various British organisations,including the [[West African Students Union]].There were also a few South Asian delegates in attendance.Also, in attendance were several \u00a0black activists living in Manchester.  Delegates included scholars, intellectuals and political activists who would later go on to become influential leaders in various [[African independence movements]] and [[Civil rights movement|American civil rights movements]]. The presence of 77-year-old [[W. E. B. Du Bois]] was historic, as he had organized the First Pan-African Congress in 1919.\n\nAmong the delegates were:\n\n* [[Jomo Kenyatta]], Kenya\n* [[W. E. B. Du Bois]], United States\n\n*[[Hastings Banda]], Malawi\n*[[Kwame Nkrumah]], Ghana\n*[[Dudley Thompson]], Jamaica\n*[[Obafemi Awolowo]] and [[Jaja Wachuku]], Nigeria\n*[[Len Johnson (boxer)|Len Johnson]], Britain\n*[[Peter Abrahams]], South Africa \u00a0\n*[[Amy Ashwood Garvey]], Jamaica\n\nIt also led partially to the creation of the [[Pan-African Federation]], founded in 1946 by Nkrumah and Kenyatta.\n\nThe British Press scarcely mentioned the conference. A number of resolutions were passed, among them the criminalization of [[racial discrimination]] and the main resolution decrying [[imperialism]] and [[capitalism]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Katzenellenbogen|first1=Simon|title=The 1945 Pan-African Congress and its Aftermath at The Manchester Civic Celebration, October 13th to 15th, 1995|url=http://www.hartford-hwp.com/archives/30/058.html|accessdate=1 March 2017|date=2 May 1995}}</ref>\n\n[[Ahmed Iqbal Ullah Race Relations Resource Centre|The Ahmed Iqbal Ullah Race Relations Resource Centre]] holds a collection of material that relates to the 5th Pan-African Congress. It spans from 1945-2005 and includes leaflets, invites, photographs, press releases, letters, a programme of events and memories from attendees captured as audio recordings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://documents.manchester.ac.uk/display.aspx?DocID=35308%20|title=Pan-African Congress 1945 and 1995 archive|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==The significance of the Pan-African movement and the Fifth Congress==\n\nPan-Africanism is aimed at the economic, intellectual and political cooperation of the African countries. It demands that the riches of the continent be used for the enlistment of its people. It calls for the financial and economic unification of markets and a new political landscape for the continent. Even though Pan-Africanism as a movement began in 1776, it was the fifth Pan-African congress that advanced Pan-Africanism and applied it to decolonize the African continent.<ref>{{cite web | title=Road to Pan-Africanism|first=Motsoko |last=Pheko| work=The Sowetan| date=15 November 1999 | url=http://www.panafricanperspective.com/pheko.htm}}</ref>\n\nThe people in Manchester were politically conscious and that was one of the reasons why it was selected as the venue for the fifth Pan-African congress. The fifth congress was organized by people of African origin living in Manchester. According to the Mancunian historian Simon Katzenellenboggen it has a great significance as it was an important step towards the end of those imperial powers in Africa. Unlike the four earlier congresses, the fifth one involved people from the African Diaspora, including Afro-Caribbeans and Afro-Americans. Manchester had a significant part to play in helping the African countries to march forward in their fight to independence.<ref>{{cite web |title=It began in Manchester \u2014 Manchester and The Pan-African Movement |publisher=BBC News; Black History Month |date=14 October 2005| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/manchester/content/articles/2005/10/14/151005_pan_african_congress_feature.shtml}}\n</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[First Pan-African Conference]]\n* [[Pan-Africanism]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Pan-African Congress}}\n* [https://snccdigital.org/our-voices/internationalism/part-4/ SNCC Digital Gateway: Organizing 6PAC] Digital documentary website created by the SNCC Legacy Project and Duke University, telling the story of the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee & grassroots organizing from the inside-out\n* [http://lucas.leeds.ac.uk/article/remembering-the-fifth-pan-african-congress-christian-hogsbjerg/ \"Remembering the Fifth Pan-African Congress - Christian H\u00f8gsbjerg], ''[[Leeds African Studies Bulletin]]'', 77 (2015\u201316). \n* B. F. Bankie, [http://www.ghanansem.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=107&Itemid=146 \"The 'Key Link' \u2013 some London notes towards the 7th Pan-African Congress\"], ''Ghana Nsem'', 2001.\n\n{{W. E. B. Du Bois|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:International conferences]]\n[[Category:Anti-racist organizations in Africa]]\n[[Category:Pan-African organizations]]\n", "name_user": "Drewellery28", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e5th Pan-African Congress:Add citations to additional information", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pan-African_Congress"}
